{"title_page": "California State Route 41", "text_new": "{{short description|Highway in California}}\n{{Redirect|CA 41|the congressional district|California's 41st congressional district}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox road\n|state=CA\n|type=SR\n|route=41\n|section=341\n|maint=[[California Department of Transportation|Caltrans]]\n|map_notes=SR 41 highlighted in red\n|length_mi=185.594\n|length_ref=<ref name=trucklist/>\n|length_round=3\n|length_notes=(plus about 6.5 mi (10.5 km) on [[California State Route 46|SR 46]], and does not include portion in [[Yosemite National Park]])\n|established=1934\n|direction_a=South\n|terminus_a={{Jct|state=CA|SR|1}} in [[Morro Bay, California|Morro Bay]]\n|junction={{plainlist\n|*{{Jct|state=CA|US|101}} in [[Atascadero, California|Atascadero]]\n*{{Jct|state=CA|SR|46}} from [[Shandon, California|Shandon]] to [[Cholame, California|Cholame]]\n*{{Jct|state=CA|I|5}} near [[Lemoore, California|Lemoore]]\n*{{Jct|state=CA|SR|198}} in [[Lemoore, California|Lemoore]]\n*{{Jct|state=CA|SR|99}} in [[Fresno, California|Fresno]]\n*{{Jct|state=CA|SR|49}} in [[Oakhurst, California|Oakhurst]]\n}}\n|direction_b=North\n|terminus_b={{Jct|state=CA|SR|140}} in [[Yosemite National Park]]\n|counties=[[San Luis Obispo County, California|San Luis Obispo]], [[Kern County, California|Kern]], [[Kings County, California|Kings]], [[Fresno County, California|Fresno]], [[Madera County, California|Madera]], [[Mariposa County, California|Mariposa]]\n|previous_type=I\n|previous_route=40\n|next_type=SR\n|next_route=42\n}}\n[[File:California's Hills along Morro bay - Atascadero Road in 1940.jpg|thumb|Morro Bay - Atascadero Road in 1940. Car is a then-new 1940 [[Lincoln-Zephyr]]. ]]\n'''State Route 41''' ('''SR 41''') is a [[state highway]] in the [[U.S. state]] of [[California]], running from the [[Cabrillo Highway]] ([[California State Route 1|SR 1]]) in [[Morro Bay, California|Morro Bay]] on the [[Central Coast (California)|Central Coast]] to  [[California State Route 140|SR 140]] in [[Yosemite National Park]], via [[Fresno, California|Fresno]] and the [[San Joaquin Valley]]. It has been constructed as an [[Limited-access road|expressway]] from near [[California State Route 198|SR 198]] in [[Lemoore, California|Lemoore]] north to the south part of [[Fresno, California|Fresno]], where the '''Yosemite Freeway''' begins, passing along the east side of downtown and extending north into [[Madera County, California|Madera County]].\n\n==Route description==\nThe majority of Route 41 runs as either two-lane rural highway or four-lane divided highway. The southern end of the highway intersects [[California State Route 1|SR 1]] in [[Morro Bay, California|Morro Bay]]. Between Morro Bay and [[Fresno, California|Fresno]], the highway intersects [[U.S. Route 101 in California|U.S. Route 101]] in [[Atascadero, California|Atascadero]], proceeds through the Coast Range and intersects [[SR 46 (CA)|SR 46]]. Actor [[James Dean]] died in an accident in 1955 at the intersection of [[California State Route 46|SR 46]] in [[Cholame, California|Cholame]]. Currently, there is a memorial located there. The interchange is now called the [[James Dean Memorial Junction]]. Between SR 46 and SR 33, SR 41 briefly travels through Kern County without any intersections in its entirety. After entering [[Kings County, California|Kings County]], it reaches [[California State Route 33|SR 33]]. SR 41 then intersects [[Interstate 5 in California|Interstate 5]] south of [[Kettleman City, California|Kettleman City]]. A large hazardous waste and [[municipal solid waste]] disposal facility operated by [[Waste Management, Inc.]] is located 5.6&nbsp;km (3.5&nbsp;mi) SSW of [[Kettleman City]] on the west side of the highway. Just before reaching the intersection at [[California State Route 198|SR 198]] outside of the city of [[Lemoore, California|Lemoore]], SR 41 becomes a four-lane divided highway until just southeast of [[Riverdale, California|Riverdale]], where SR 41 reverts to one lane in each direction. The El Adobe de los Robles Rancho built by pioneer [[Daniel Rhoads]] can be found north of Lemoore.\n\nSoutheast of [[Caruthers, California|Caruthers]], SR 41 becomes a four-lane divided highway and eventually a freeway approaching the Fresno city limits. The route intersects [[California State Route 99|SR 99]] near Jensen Avenue. Complete access is not available between SR 41/SR 99. For example, there is no direct connector between the southbound SR 41 and northbound SR 99; drivers wanting to make this transition must exit at the SR 41/SR 180 interchange, head west on SR 180, and then transition onto SR 99 at the interchange between those two freeways. Likewise, there is no direct connector between the northbound SR 41 and the southbound SR 99. Drivers must exit at Jensen Avenue, head east on Jensen until its junction with SR 99 a half-mile east of SR 41, and then make the southbound transition onto SR 99.\n\nSR 41 continues north into downtown Fresno, then intersects [[California State Route 180|SR 180]] at a section of the latter route that links SR 41 to both SR 99 to the west, and to [[California State Route 168|SR 168]] to the east. North of Fresno, the route crosses the San Joaquin River, and enters [[Madera County, California|Madera County]] near [[Children's Hospital Central California|Children's Hospital of Central California]] before reverting to a two-lane highway. {{convert|8.5|mi|km}} further north, Route 41 intersects with [[California State Route 145|SR 145]], before entering California's [[Sierra Nevada (U.S.)|Sierra-Nevada]] mountain range. Route 41 continues through the towns of [[Coarsegold, California|Coarsegold]] and [[Oakhurst, California|Oakhurst]], where it intersects with [[California State Route 49|SR 49]]. Route 41 ends in [[Yosemite National Park]] to the north.\n\n[[File:Wawona Tunnel and SR-41.JPG|thumb|upright|East portal of Wawona Tunnel near eastern terminus of SR 41]]\n[[Tunnel View]] is a viewpoint located just outside the east end of the Wawona Tunnel in Yosemite National Park. It is located about 1.5 miles (2.4&nbsp;km) from the [[Yosemite Valley]]. This is the first view that most people have of Yosemite Valley. There is an END-41 sign just south of the southern entrance to [[Yosemite National Park]]. The state routes within the park are not signed (with the exception of [[California State Route 120|SR 120]]). Tunnel View is along Route 41's alignment, although state maintenance of the route ends at the south entrance of the park.\n\nExcept between [[U.S. Route 101 in California|US 101]] in [[Atascadero, California|Atascadero]] and [[California State Route 46|SR 46]] near [[Shandon, California|Shandon]], SR 41 is part of the [[California Freeway and Expressway System]],<ref name=\"cafes\">{{CAFESystem}}</ref> and north of SR 46 is part of the [[National Highway System (United States)|National Highway System]],<ref name=fhwa-nhs>{{FHWA NHS map|region=californiasouth|accessdate=October 15, 2017}}</ref> a network of highways that are considered essential to the country's economy, defense, and mobility by the [[Federal Highway Administration]].<ref name=NHS-FHWA>{{FHWA NHS}}</ref> Three segments{{spaced ndash}}from SR 1 to US 101, SR 46 to [[California State Route 33|SR 33]], and [[California State Route 49|SR 49]] at [[Oakhurst, California|Oakhurst]] to Yosemite (the Wawona Road){{spaced ndash}}are eligible for inclusion in the [[State Scenic Highway System (California)|State Scenic Highway System]],<ref name=\"scenic\">{{CA scenic}}</ref> but SR 41 is not officially designated as a scenic highway by the [[California Department of Transportation]].<ref name=\"caltransscenic\">{{Caltrans scenic|accessdate=October 15, 2017}}</ref> SR 41 is known as the [[Edward Gardner Lewis|E.G. Lewis]] Highway from SR 1 to US 101 in San Luis Obispo County, the Dwight David Eisenhower Memorial Freeway from Ventura Avenue in Fresno to Herndon Avenue in Fresno, the Donald DeMers Highway from Jensen Avenue in Fresno to Elkhorn Avenue, the Yosemite Freeway from Elkhorn Avenue to the Fresno-Madera County line, the Southern Yosemite Highway from the Fresno-Madera County line to Yosemite National Park, and the Wawona Road from Fresno to Yosemite National Park.<ref>{{CA Named Freeways | pages=40\u201341}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Cal State Route 41.jpg|thumb|Northbound on Route 41 in Fresno at the [[California State Route 180|Route 180]] interchange]]\nIn 1930, the counties of [[Fresno County, California|Fresno]], [[Kings County, California|Kings]], [[Kern County, California|Kern]], and [[San Luis Obispo County, California|San Luis Obispo]] considered organizing<!--they didn't actually organize one&nbsp;\u2014 see [[Wikipedia:WikiProject California State Highways/History/Joint Highway Districts]]--> a [[joint highway district]] to construct a shortcut connecting [[Fresno, California|Fresno]] with the [[Pacific Ocean]] at [[Morro Bay, California|Morro Bay]]. This highway would pass through [[Kettleman City, California|Kettleman City]] on its way to the [[Cholame Lateral]] ([[Legislative Route 33 (California pre-1964)|Legislative Route 33]]) near [[Cholame, California|Cholame]] or [[Shandon, California|Shandon]], and then continue to Morro Bay, where a new [[harbor]] was being developed.<ref>[[Los Angeles Times]], Morro Bay Road Looms, April 26, 1930, p. 4</ref><ref>[[Fresno Bee]], Fresno-To-Coast Highway Proposal Looks Favorable, May 7, 1930</ref> The entire length from Fresno to Morro Bay, as well as the Wawona Road to Yosemite, was added to the state highway system in 1933 as '''Route 125''',<ref>{{cite CAstat|year=1933|ch=767|p=2037, 2038}}: \"State Highway Route 4 near Fresno to Yosemite National Park.\" \"State Highway Route 56 near Moro [sic] to State Highway Route 4 near Fresno via Stratford.\"</ref><ref>{{cite CAstat|year=1935|ch=29|p=283, 284}}: \"Route 125 is from: (a) Route 56 near Morro to Route 4 near Fresno via Stratford. (b) Route 4 near Fresno to Yosemite National Park.\"</ref> and subsequently improved by the state.<!--I cannot find any details at all on when this was done--> In 1934, the state sign route system was established, and '''Sign Route 41''' was designated along Route 125 from Yosemite south and southwest to Cholame and then west through [[Paso Robles, California|Paso Robles]] to [[Cambria, California|Cambria]] via [[Legislative Route 33 (California pre-1964)|Legislative Route 33]].<ref>California Highways and Public Works, [http://www.gbcnet.com/roads/ca_routes_1934.html State Routes will be Numbered and Marked with Distinctive Bear Signs], August 1934</ref> The part of Route 125 southwest of Cholame instead became part of the new [[U.S. Route 466 in California|U.S. Route 466]].<ref>Richard F. Weingroff, [http://www.fhwa.dot.gov/infrastructure/us666.htm U.S. 666: \"Beast of a Highway\"?]</ref>\n\nBy the 1950s, the short piece of US 466 (Route 125) between [[Creston, California|Creston]] and [[Atascadero, California|Atascadero]] had not yet been paved, and so US 466 was moved to the longer but better road via Paso Robles, replacing SR 41 to Paso Robles and [[overlap (road)|overlapping]] [[U.S. Route 101 in California|US 101]] to Atascadero. As SR 41 had not been signed over the unpaved road west of Paso Robles, it was truncated to Cholame.<ref>[[H.M. Gousha Company]], [http://members.cox.net/mkpl2/hist/mp55-centralvly.jpg California] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071231013137/http://members.cox.net/mkpl2/hist/mp55-centralvly.jpg |date=December 31, 2007 }}, 1955</ref> US 466 was eliminated in the [[1964 renumbering (California)|1964 renumbering]], becoming [[California State Route 46|SR 46]] east from Paso Robles. However, instead of going south and west to Morro Bay, SR 46 continued west to Cambria, and the road via Creston and Atascadero to Morro Bay (which had since been paved) became part of SR 41.<ref>[[H.M. Gousha Company]], California, 1963</ref><ref name=\"law-renumbering\">{{cite CAstat|year=1963|ch=385|p=1175}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1980s, the urban stretch of 41 running through [[Fresno, California|Fresno]] was upgraded to freeway standards, intersecting [[California State Route 99|SR 99]] to the south. In the late 1990s and early 2000s, the freeway portion was extended several miles beyond Fresno in both directions.\n\nAlso in the late 1990s and early 2000s in Atascadero, the old SR 41 alignment used to cut through downtown by going north on El Camino Real and turning right onto West Mall. Then it continued past the Atascadero Colony Building and crossed the 1921 Atascadero Creek Bridge before turning left onto Capistrano Avenue. It then went under a low clearance railroad crossing and a dangerous narrow bridge crossing the Salinas River before rejoining its existing alignment. Then Caltrans built a bypass of this dangerous route with a long wider bridge crossing the railroad, Sycamore Drive, and the river before joining the original 1950s SR 41. SR 41 is now currently signed on this bypass. Since then, the old bridge was demolished but the railroad undercrossing still remains. There's an old sign on Capistrano Avenue that still marks it as \"Hwy 41\" and signs on El Camino Real that mark West Mall with covered up \"41\" shields.\n\n==Future==\nThe Kings County Association of Governments has plans to improve the state highways within the county. Developers are interested in building distribution warehouses in Kings County because of its strategic location midway between the Los Angeles and San Francisco Bay areas, but they are currently turned off by the lack of freeway access. For SR 41, the plan is to upgrade it so the highway is a continuous freeway from I-5 north to Fresno County. However, Kings County voters have shown little interest in passing any transportation taxes to fund these projects.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://hanfordsentinel.com/news/local/road-map-for-the-future/article_f1222a8e-17e1-11e3-9878-001a4bcf887a.html | title=Road map for the future? | first=Seth | last=Nidever | work=The Sentinel | date=September 7, 2013 | accessdate=March 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Major intersections==\n{{CAinttop|exit|post_ref=<br><ref name=trucklist /><ref name=bridgelog>{{Caltrans bridgelog|date=July 2007}}</ref><ref>[[California Department of Transportation]], [http://traffic-counts.dot.ca.gov/ All Traffic Volumes on CSHS], 2005 and 2006</ref>|exit_ref=<br><ref>[[California Department of Transportation]], [[California Numbered Exit Uniform System]], [http://www.dot.ca.gov/trafficops/exit/docs/41.pdf State Route 41 Freeway Interchanges], Retrieved on February 5, 2009.</ref>|San Gabriel Road=|postsmile=14|CAint=}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|county=San Luis Obispo\n|cspan=8\n|location=Morro Bay\n|lspan=2\n|county_note=SLO 0.00-50.43\n|postmile=0.00\n|road=Atascadero Road\n|notes=Continuation beyond SR 1\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=0.00\n|road={{jct|state=CA|SR|1|city1=Cayucos|city2=Cambria|location3=[[Hearst Castle]]}}\n|notes=Interchange; south end of SR 41; SR 1 exit 279B\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|location=Atascadero\n|lspan=2\n|postmile=15.89\n|road={{jct|state=CA|US|101|city1=San Francisco|city2=Los Angeles}}\n|notes=Interchange; US 101 exit 219\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=15.96\n|road=[[El Camino Real (California)|El Camino Real]]\n|notes=\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|location=none\n|postmile=27.98\n|road={{jct|state=CA|SR|229|dir1=south|city1=Creston}}\n|notes=\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|location=Shandon\n|postmile=41.16\n|line=yes\n|postmile2=48.63<ref group=\"N\" name=\"SR 46\">Indicates that the postmile represents the distance along [[California State Route 46|SR 46]] rather than SR 41.</ref>\n|road={{jct|state=CA|SR|46|dir1=west|city1=Paso Robles|road=McMillian Canyon Road}}\n|notes=South end of SR 46 overlap\n|type=concur\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|location=none\n|postmile=49.60<ref group=\"N\" name=\"SR 46\"/>\n|place=Shandon Rest Area\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|location=Cholame\n|postmile=55.11<ref group=\"N\" name=\"SR 46\"/>\n|line=yes\n|postmile2=43.85\n|road={{jct|state=CA|SR|46|dir1=east|city1=Bakersfield}}\n|notes=North end of SR 46 overlap; former [[U.S. Route 466 in California|US 466]] east\n|type=concur\n}}\n{{Jctco|exit\n|state=CA\n|county=Kern\n|county_note=KER 0.00-4.98\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|county=Kings\n|cspan=7\n|county_note=KIN 0.00-R48.28\n|location=none\n|postmile=8.10\n|road={{jct|state=CA|SR|33|city1=Avenal|city2=Taft}}\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|location=none\n|postmile=16.28\n|road={{jct|state=CA|I|5|city1=Sacramento|city2=Los Angeles}}\n|notes=Interchange; I-5 exit 309\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|location=Lemoore\n|lspan=4\n|postmile=R39.96\n|road={{jct|state=CA|SR|198|city1=Hanford|city2=Sequoia Park|city3=Coalinga|location4=[[Naval Air Station Lemoore|Lemoore NAS]]}}\n|notes=Interchange; SR 198 exit 77\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=none\n|place=South end of freeway\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=R40.95\n|road=Bush Street\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=none\n|place=North end of freeway\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|location=none\n|postmile=R48.28\n|road=Excelsior Avenue\n|notes=Interchange\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|county=Fresno\n|cspan=18\n|county_note=FRE R0.00-33.45\n|location=none\n|postmile=none\n|road={{jct|state=CA|SR-Bus|41|dir1=north|dab1=Easton|name1=Adams Avenue|city1=Easton}}\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|location=none\n|postmile=none\n|road={{jct|state=CA|SR-Bus|41|dir1=south|dab1=Easton|name1=American Avenue|city1=Easton}}\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|location=none\n|postmile=none\n|place=South end of freeway\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|location=Fresno\n|lspan=15\n|postmile=R20.11\n|exit=124\n|road=North Avenue\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=R21.13\n|exit=125\n|road=Jensen Avenue\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=R21.90\n|exit=126A\n|road={{jct|state=CA|SR|99|dir1=north|city1=Madera|city2=Sacramento}}\n|notes=Northbound exit and southbound entrance; SR 99 south exit 131\n|type=incomplete\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=R21.90\n|exit=126A\n|road={{jct|state=CA|SR|99|dir1=south|city1=Bakersfield|city2=Los Angeles}}\n|notes=Southbound exit and northbound entrance; SR 99 north exit 131\n|type=incomplete\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=R22.80\n|exit=126B\n|road=Van Ness Avenue \u2013 Civic Center\n|notes=Former [[California State Route 180|SR 180]]\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=R22.95\n|exit=127A\n|road=O Street\n|notes=Southbound exit only\n|type=incomplete\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=R23.74\n|exit=127B\n|road=Tulare Street, Divisadero Street\n|notes=Signed as exit 127 northbound\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=R24.53\n|exit=128\n|road={{jct|state=CA|SR|168|dir1=east|name1=[[Sierra Freeway]]|SR|180|name2=[[Sequoia-Kings Canyon Freeway]]|city1=Clovis|city2=Huntington Lake|city3=Kings Canyon|city4=Mendota}}\n|notes=Signed as exits 128A (east) and 128B (west) northbound; SR 168 exit 1A; SR 180 exits 59A-B\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=R25.26\n|exit=129\n|road=McKinley Avenue\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=R26.46\n|exit=130\n|road=Shields Avenue\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=R27.47\n|exit=131\n|road=Ashlan Avenue\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=R28.47\n|exit=132\n|road=Shaw Avenue&nbsp;\u2013 [[Clovis, California|Clovis]]\n|notes=Former [[California State Route 168|SR 168]]; serves [[California State University, Fresno|California State University Fresno]]\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=R29.46\n|exit=133\n|road=Bullard Avenue\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=R30.45\n|exit=134\n|road=Herndon Avenue&nbsp;\u2013 [[Clovis, California|Clovis]]\n|notes=Connects to [[California State Route 99|SR 99]] north\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=R31.68\n|exit=135\n|road=Friant Road, Blackstone Avenue&nbsp;\u2013 [[Millerton Lake]]\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|county=Madera\n|cspan=5\n|county_note=MAD 0.00-45.74\n|location=none\n|postmile=R1.20\n|exit=138\n|road=Rio Mesa Boulevard, Children's Boulevard ([[California State Route 41 Business|SR 41 Bus.]] north)\n|notes=Signed as exits 138A (Rio Mesa Boulevard) and 138B (Children's Boulevard) northbound\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|location=none\n|postmile=none\n|place=North end of freeway\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|location=none\n|postmile=3.23\n|road={{jct|state=CA|SR-Bus|41|dir1=south|name1=Avenue 12|city1=Madera Ranchos}}\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|location=none\n|postmile=9.25\n|road={{jct|state=CA|SR|145|dir1=south|to2=yes|SR|99|dir2=north|road=Road 145|city1=Madera|location2=[[Millerton Lake]]}}\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|location=Oakhurst\n|postmile=35.48\n|road={{jct|state=CA|SR|49|dir1=north|city1=Ahwahnee|city2=Mariposa}}\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|county=Mariposa\n|cspan=4\n|county_note=MPA 0.00-4.92\n|location=Fish Camp\n|postmile=4.92\n|place=North end of Highway 41 at [[Yosemite National Park]] south entrance\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|location=none\n|postmile=none\n|place=[[Wawona Tunnel]]\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|location=none\n|type=incomplete\n|postmile=none\n|road={{jct|state=CA|SR|140|dir1=east}}\n|notes=Entrance only\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|location=none\n|type=incomplete\n|postmile=none\n|exit=\n|road=Southside Drive\n|notes=Continuation beyond SR 140; southbound entrance only accessible via Northside Drive to SR 140\n}}\n{{Jctbtm|col=6|keys=concur,incomplete}}\n{{reflist|group=\"N\"}}\n\n==See also==\n*{{portal-inline|California Roads}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Attached KML|display=inline,title}}\n{{Commons category|California State Route 41}}{{wikisource|Wawona Road (HAER No. CA-148) written historical and descriptive data}}\n* [http://www.aaroads.com/california/ca-041.html California @ AARoads.com - State Route 41]\n* [http://www.dot.ca.gov/hq/roadinfo/sr41 Caltrans: Route 41 highway conditions]\n* [http://www.cahighways.org/041-048.html#041 California Highways: Route 41]\n\n{{Yosemite National Park}}\n\n[[Category:State highways in California|041]]\n[[Category:Freeways in California|041]]\n[[Category:Roads in Kern County, California|State Route 041]]\n[[Category:Roads in Kings County, California|State Route 041]]\n[[Category:Roads in Fresno County, California|State Route 041]]\n[[Category:Roads in Madera County, California|State Route 041]]\n[[Category:Roads in Mariposa County, California|State Route 041]]\n[[Category:Roads in San Luis Obispo County, California|State Route 041]]\n[[Category:Yosemite National Park]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Highway in California}}\n{{Redirect|CA 41|the congressional district|California's 41st congressional district}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox road\n|state=CA\n|type=SR\n|route=41\n|section=341\n|maint=[[California Department of Transportation|Caltrans]]\n|map_notes=SR 41 highlighted in red\n|length_mi=185.594\n|length_ref=<ref name=trucklist/>\n|length_round=3\n|length_notes=(plus about 6.5 mi (10.5 km) on [[California State Route 46|SR 46]], and does not include portion in [[Yosemite National Park]])\n|established=1934\n|direction_a=South\n|terminus_a={{Jct|state=CA|SR|1}} in [[Morro Bay, California|Morro Bay]]\n|junction={{plainlist\n|*{{Jct|state=CA|US|101}} in [[Atascadero, California|Atascadero]]\n*{{Jct|state=CA|SR|46}} from [[Shandon, California|Shandon]] to [[Cholame, California|Cholame]]\n*{{Jct|state=CA|I|5}} near [[Lemoore, California|Lemoore]]\n*{{Jct|state=CA|SR|198}} in [[Lemoore, California|Lemoore]]\n*{{Jct|state=CA|SR|99}} in [[Fresno, California|Fresno]]\n*{{Jct|state=CA|SR|49}} in [[Oakhurst, California|Oakhurst]]\n}}\n|direction_b=North\n|terminus_b={{Jct|state=CA|SR|140}} in [[Yosemite National Park]]\n|counties=[[San Luis Obispo County, California|San Luis Obispo]], [[Kern County, California|Kern]], [[Kings County, California|Kings]], [[Fresno County, California|Fresno]], [[Madera County, California|Madera]], [[Mariposa County, California|Mariposa]]\n|previous_type=I\n|previous_route=40\n|next_type=SR\n|next_route=42\n}}\n[[File:California's Hills along Morro bay - Atascadero Road in 1940.jpg|thumb|Morro Bay - Atascadero Road in 1940. Car is a then-new 1940 [[Lincoln-Zephyr]]. ]]\n'''State Route 41''' ('''SR 41''') is a [[state highway]] in the [[U.S. state]] of [[California]], running from the [[Cabrillo Highway]] ([[California State Route 1|SR 1]]) in [[Morro Bay, California|Morro Bay]] on the [[Central Coast (California)|Central Coast]] to  [[California State Route 140|SR 140]] in [[Yosemite National Park]], via [[Fresno, California|Fresno]] and the [[San Joaquin Valley]]. It has been constructed as an [[Limited-access road|expressway]] from near [[California State Route 198|SR 198]] in [[Lemoore, California|Lemoore]] north to the south part of [[Fresno, California|Fresno]], where the '''Yosemite Freeway''' begins, passing along the east side of downtown and extending north into [[Madera County, California|Madera County]].\n\n==Route description==\nThe majority of Route 41 runs as either two-lane rural highway or four-lane divided highway. The southern end of the highway intersects [[California State Route 1|SR 1]] in [[Morro Bay, California|Morro Bay]]. Between Morro Bay and [[Fresno, California|Fresno]], the highway intersects [[U.S. Route 101 in California|U.S. Route 101]] in [[Atascadero, California|Atascadero]], proceeds through the Coast Range and intersects [[SR 46 (CA)|SR 46]]. Actor [[James Dean]] died in an accident in 1955 at the intersection of [[California State Route 46|SR 46]] in [[Cholame, California|Cholame]]. Currently, there is a memorial located there. The interchange is now called the [[James Dean Memorial Junction]]. Between SR 46 and SR 33, SR 41 briefly travels through Kern County without any intersections in its entirety. After entering [[Kings County, California|Kings County]], it reaches [[California State Route 33|SR 33]]. SR 41 then intersects [[Interstate 5 in California|Interstate 5]] south of [[Kettleman City, California|Kettleman City]]. A large hazardous waste and [[municipal solid waste]] disposal facility operated by [[Waste Management, Inc.]] is located 5.6&nbsp;km (3.5&nbsp;mi) SSW of [[Kettleman City]] on the west side of the highway. Just before reaching the intersection at [[California State Route 198|SR 198]] outside of the city of [[Lemoore, California|Lemoore]], SR 41 becomes a four-lane divided highway until just southeast of [[Riverdale, California|Riverdale]], where SR 41 reverts to one lane in each direction. The El Adobe de los Robles Rancho built by pioneer [[Daniel Rhoads]] can be found north of Lemoore.\n\nSoutheast of [[Caruthers, California|Caruthers]], SR 41 becomes a four-lane divided highway and eventually a freeway approaching the Fresno city limits. The route intersects [[California State Route 99|SR 99]] near Jensen Avenue. Complete access is not available between SR 41/SR 99. For example, there is no direct connector between the southbound SR 41 and northbound SR 99; drivers wanting to make this transition must exit at the SR 41/SR 180 interchange, head west on SR 180, and then transition onto SR 99 at the interchange between those two freeways. Likewise, there is no direct connector between the northbound SR 41 and the southbound SR 99. Drivers must exit at Jensen Avenue, head east on Jensen until its junction with SR 99 a half-mile east of SR 41, and then make the southbound transition onto SR 99.\n\nSR 41 continues north into downtown Fresno, then intersects [[California State Route 180|SR 180]] at a section of the latter route that links SR 41 to both SR 99 to the west, and to [[California State Route 168|SR 168]] to the east. North of Fresno, the route crosses the San Joaquin River, and enters [[Madera County, California|Madera County]] near [[Children's Hospital Central California|Children's Hospital of Central California]] before reverting to a two-lane highway. {{convert|8.5|mi|km}} further north, Route 41 intersects with [[California State Route 145|SR 145]], before entering California's [[Sierra Nevada (U.S.)|Sierra-Nevada]] mountain range. Route 41 continues through the towns of [[Coarsegold, California|Coarsegold]] and [[Oakhurst, California|Oakhurst]], where it intersects with [[California State Route 49|SR 49]]. Route 41 ends in [[Yosemite National Park]] to the north.\n\n[[File:Wawona Tunnel and SR-41.JPG|thumb|upright|East portal of Wawona Tunnel near eastern terminus of SR 41]]\n[[Tunnel View]] is a viewpoint located just outside the east end of the Wawona Tunnel in Yosemite National Park. It is located about 1.5 miles (2.4&nbsp;km) from the [[Yosemite Valley]]. This is the first view that most people have of Yosemite Valley. There is an END-41 sign just south of the southern entrance to [[Yosemite National Park]]. The state routes within the park are not signed (with the exception of [[California State Route 120|SR 120]]). Tunnel View is along Route 41's alignment, although state maintenance of the route ends at the south entrance of the park.\n\nExcept between [[U.S. Route 101 in California|US 101]] in [[Atascadero, California|Atascadero]] and [[California State Route 46|SR 46]] near [[Shandon, California|Shandon]], SR 41 is part of the [[California Freeway and Expressway System]],<ref name=\"cafes\">{{CAFESystem}}</ref> and north of SR 46 is part of the [[National Highway System (United States)|National Highway System]],<ref name=fhwa-nhs>{{FHWA NHS map|region=californiasouth|accessdate=October 15, 2017}}</ref> a network of highways that are considered essential to the country's economy, defense, and mobility by the [[Federal Highway Administration]].<ref name=NHS-FHWA>{{FHWA NHS}}</ref> Three segments{{spaced ndash}}from SR 1 to US 101, SR 46 to [[California State Route 33|SR 33]], and [[California State Route 49|SR 49]] at [[Oakhurst, California|Oakhurst]] to Yosemite (the Wawona Road){{spaced ndash}}are eligible for inclusion in the [[State Scenic Highway System (California)|State Scenic Highway System]],<ref name=\"scenic\">{{CA scenic}}</ref> but SR 41 is not officially designated as a scenic highway by the [[California Department of Transportation]].<ref name=\"caltransscenic\">{{Caltrans scenic|accessdate=October 15, 2017}}</ref> SR 41 is known as the [[Edward Gardner Lewis|E.G. Lewis]] Highway from SR 1 to US 101 in San Luis Obispo County, the Dwight David Eisenhower Memorial Freeway from Ventura Avenue in Fresno to Herndon Avenue in Fresno, the Donald DeMers Highway from Jensen Avenue in Fresno to Elkhorn Avenue, the Yosemite Freeway from Elkhorn Avenue to the Fresno-Madera County line, the Southern Yosemite Highway from the Fresno-Madera County line to Yosemite National Park, and the Wawona Road from Fresno to Yosemite National Park.<ref>{{CA Named Freeways | pages=40\u201341}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Cal State Route 41.jpg|thumb|Northbound on Route 41 in Fresno at the [[California State Route 180|Route 180]] interchange]]\nIn 1930, the counties of [[Fresno County, California|Fresno]], [[Kings County, California|Kings]], [[Kern County, California|Kern]], and [[San Luis Obispo County, California|San Luis Obispo]] considered organizing<!--they didn't actually organize one&nbsp;\u2014 see [[Wikipedia:WikiProject California State Highways/History/Joint Highway Districts]]--> a [[joint highway district]] to construct a shortcut connecting [[Fresno, California|Fresno]] with the [[Pacific Ocean]] at [[Morro Bay, California|Morro Bay]]. This highway would pass through [[Kettleman City, California|Kettleman City]] on its way to the [[Cholame Lateral]] ([[Legislative Route 33 (California pre-1964)|Legislative Route 33]]) near [[Cholame, California|Cholame]] or [[Shandon, California|Shandon]], and then continue to Morro Bay, where a new [[harbor]] was being developed.<ref>[[Los Angeles Times]], Morro Bay Road Looms, April 26, 1930, p. 4</ref><ref>[[Fresno Bee]], Fresno-To-Coast Highway Proposal Looks Favorable, May 7, 1930</ref> The entire length from Fresno to Morro Bay, as well as the Wawona Road to Yosemite, was added to the state highway system in 1933 as '''Route 125''',<ref>{{cite CAstat|year=1933|ch=767|p=2037, 2038}}: \"State Highway Route 4 near Fresno to Yosemite National Park.\" \"State Highway Route 56 near Moro [sic] to State Highway Route 4 near Fresno via Stratford.\"</ref><ref>{{cite CAstat|year=1935|ch=29|p=283, 284}}: \"Route 125 is from: (a) Route 56 near Morro to Route 4 near Fresno via Stratford. (b) Route 4 near Fresno to Yosemite National Park.\"</ref> and subsequently improved by the state.<!--I cannot find any details at all on when this was done--> In 1934, the state sign route system was established, and '''Sign Route 41''' was designated along Route 125 from Yosemite south and southwest to Cholame and then west through [[Paso Robles, California|Paso Robles]] to [[Cambria, California|Cambria]] via [[Legislative Route 33 (California pre-1964)|Legislative Route 33]].<ref>California Highways and Public Works, [http://www.gbcnet.com/roads/ca_routes_1934.html State Routes will be Numbered and Marked with Distinctive Bear Signs], August 1934</ref> The part of Route 125 southwest of Cholame instead became part of the new [[U.S. Route 466 in California|U.S. Route 466]].<ref>Richard F. Weingroff, [http://www.fhwa.dot.gov/infrastructure/us666.htm U.S. 666: \"Beast of a Highway\"?]</ref>\n\nBy the 1950s, the short piece of US 466 (Route 125) between [[Creston, California|Creston]] and [[Atascadero, California|Atascadero]] had not yet been paved, and so US 466 was moved to the longer but better road via Paso Robles, replacing SR 41 to Paso Robles and [[overlap (road)|overlapping]] [[U.S. Route 101 in California|US 101]] to Atascadero. As SR 41 had not been signed over the unpaved road west of Paso Robles, it was truncated to Cholame.<ref>[[H.M. Gousha Company]], [http://members.cox.net/mkpl2/hist/mp55-centralvly.jpg California] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071231013137/http://members.cox.net/mkpl2/hist/mp55-centralvly.jpg |date=December 31, 2007 }}, 1955</ref> US 466 was eliminated in the [[1964 renumbering (California)|1964 renumbering]], becoming [[California State Route 46|SR 46]] east from Paso Robles. However, instead of going south and west to Morro Bay, SR 46 continued west to Cambria, and the road via Creston and Atascadero to Morro Bay (which had since been paved) became part of SR 41.<ref>[[H.M. Gousha Company]], California, 1963</ref><ref name=\"law-renumbering\">{{cite CAstat|year=1963|ch=385|p=1175}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1980s, the urban stretch of 41 running through [[Fresno, California|Fresno]] was upgraded to freeway standards, intersecting [[California State Route 99|SR 99]] to the south. In the late 1990s and early 2000s, the freeway portion was extended several miles beyond Fresno in both directions.\n\nAlso in the late 1990's and early 2000's in Atascadero, the old SR 41 alignment used to cut through downtown by going north on El Camino Real and turning right onto West Mall. Then it continued past the Atascadero Colony Building and crossed the 1921 Atascadero Creek Bridge before turning left onto Capistrano Avenue. It then went under a low clearance railroad crossing and a dangerous narrow bridge crossing the Salinas River before rejoining its existing alignment. Then Caltrans built a bypass of this dangerous route with a long wider bridge crossing the railroad, Sycamore Drive, and the river before joining the original 1950's SR 41. SR 41 is now currently signed on this bypass. Since then, the old bridge was demolished but the railroad undercrossing still remains. There's an old sign on Capistrano Avenue that still marks it as \"Hwy 41\" and signs on El Camino Real that mark West Mall with covered up \"41\" shields.\n\n==Future==\nThe Kings County Association of Governments has plans to improve the state highways within the county. Developers are interested in building distribution warehouses in Kings County because of its strategic location midway between the Los Angeles and San Francisco Bay areas, but they are currently turned off by the lack of freeway access. For SR 41, the plan is to upgrade it so the highway is a continuous freeway from I-5 north to Fresno County. However, Kings County voters have shown little interest in passing any transportation taxes to fund these projects.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://hanfordsentinel.com/news/local/road-map-for-the-future/article_f1222a8e-17e1-11e3-9878-001a4bcf887a.html | title=Road map for the future? | first=Seth | last=Nidever | work=The Sentinel | date=September 7, 2013 | accessdate=March 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Major intersections==\n{{CAinttop|exit|post_ref=<br><ref name=trucklist /><ref name=bridgelog>{{Caltrans bridgelog|date=July 2007}}</ref><ref>[[California Department of Transportation]], [http://traffic-counts.dot.ca.gov/ All Traffic Volumes on CSHS], 2005 and 2006</ref>|exit_ref=<br><ref>[[California Department of Transportation]], [[California Numbered Exit Uniform System]], [http://www.dot.ca.gov/trafficops/exit/docs/41.pdf State Route 41 Freeway Interchanges], Retrieved on February 5, 2009.</ref>|San Gabriel Road=|postsmile=14|CAint=}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|county=San Luis Obispo\n|cspan=8\n|location=Morro Bay\n|lspan=2\n|county_note=SLO 0.00-50.43\n|postmile=0.00\n|road=Atascadero Road\n|notes=Continuation beyond SR 1\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=0.00\n|road={{jct|state=CA|SR|1|city1=Cayucos|city2=Cambria|location3=[[Hearst Castle]]}}\n|notes=Interchange; south end of SR 41; SR 1 exit 279B\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|location=Atascadero\n|lspan=2\n|postmile=15.89\n|road={{jct|state=CA|US|101|city1=San Francisco|city2=Los Angeles}}\n|notes=Interchange; US 101 exit 219\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=15.96\n|road=[[El Camino Real (California)|El Camino Real]]\n|notes=\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|location=none\n|postmile=27.98\n|road={{jct|state=CA|SR|229|dir1=south|city1=Creston}}\n|notes=\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|location=Shandon\n|postmile=41.16\n|line=yes\n|postmile2=48.63<ref group=\"N\" name=\"SR 46\">Indicates that the postmile represents the distance along [[California State Route 46|SR 46]] rather than SR 41.</ref>\n|road={{jct|state=CA|SR|46|dir1=west|city1=Paso Robles|road=McMillian Canyon Road}}\n|notes=South end of SR 46 overlap\n|type=concur\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|location=none\n|postmile=49.60<ref group=\"N\" name=\"SR 46\"/>\n|place=Shandon Rest Area\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|location=Cholame\n|postmile=55.11<ref group=\"N\" name=\"SR 46\"/>\n|line=yes\n|postmile2=43.85\n|road={{jct|state=CA|SR|46|dir1=east|city1=Bakersfield}}\n|notes=North end of SR 46 overlap; former [[U.S. Route 466 in California|US 466]] east\n|type=concur\n}}\n{{Jctco|exit\n|state=CA\n|county=Kern\n|county_note=KER 0.00-4.98\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|county=Kings\n|cspan=7\n|county_note=KIN 0.00-R48.28\n|location=none\n|postmile=8.10\n|road={{jct|state=CA|SR|33|city1=Avenal|city2=Taft}}\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|location=none\n|postmile=16.28\n|road={{jct|state=CA|I|5|city1=Sacramento|city2=Los Angeles}}\n|notes=Interchange; I-5 exit 309\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|location=Lemoore\n|lspan=4\n|postmile=R39.96\n|road={{jct|state=CA|SR|198|city1=Hanford|city2=Sequoia Park|city3=Coalinga|location4=[[Naval Air Station Lemoore|Lemoore NAS]]}}\n|notes=Interchange; SR 198 exit 77\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=none\n|place=South end of freeway\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=R40.95\n|road=Bush Street\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=none\n|place=North end of freeway\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|location=none\n|postmile=R48.28\n|road=Excelsior Avenue\n|notes=Interchange\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|county=Fresno\n|cspan=18\n|county_note=FRE R0.00-33.45\n|location=none\n|postmile=none\n|road={{jct|state=CA|SR-Bus|41|dir1=north|dab1=Easton|name1=Adams Avenue|city1=Easton}}\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|location=none\n|postmile=none\n|road={{jct|state=CA|SR-Bus|41|dir1=south|dab1=Easton|name1=American Avenue|city1=Easton}}\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|location=none\n|postmile=none\n|place=South end of freeway\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|location=Fresno\n|lspan=15\n|postmile=R20.11\n|exit=124\n|road=North Avenue\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=R21.13\n|exit=125\n|road=Jensen Avenue\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=R21.90\n|exit=126A\n|road={{jct|state=CA|SR|99|dir1=north|city1=Madera|city2=Sacramento}}\n|notes=Northbound exit and southbound entrance; SR 99 south exit 131\n|type=incomplete\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=R21.90\n|exit=126A\n|road={{jct|state=CA|SR|99|dir1=south|city1=Bakersfield|city2=Los Angeles}}\n|notes=Southbound exit and northbound entrance; SR 99 north exit 131\n|type=incomplete\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=R22.80\n|exit=126B\n|road=Van Ness Avenue \u2013 Civic Center\n|notes=Former [[California State Route 180|SR 180]]\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=R22.95\n|exit=127A\n|road=O Street\n|notes=Southbound exit only\n|type=incomplete\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=R23.74\n|exit=127B\n|road=Tulare Street, Divisadero Street\n|notes=Signed as exit 127 northbound\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=R24.53\n|exit=128\n|road={{jct|state=CA|SR|168|dir1=east|name1=[[Sierra Freeway]]|SR|180|name2=[[Sequoia-Kings Canyon Freeway]]|city1=Clovis|city2=Huntington Lake|city3=Kings Canyon|city4=Mendota}}\n|notes=Signed as exits 128A (east) and 128B (west) northbound; SR 168 exit 1A; SR 180 exits 59A-B\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=R25.26\n|exit=129\n|road=McKinley Avenue\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=R26.46\n|exit=130\n|road=Shields Avenue\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=R27.47\n|exit=131\n|road=Ashlan Avenue\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=R28.47\n|exit=132\n|road=Shaw Avenue&nbsp;\u2013 [[Clovis, California|Clovis]]\n|notes=Former [[California State Route 168|SR 168]]; serves [[California State University, Fresno|California State University Fresno]]\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=R29.46\n|exit=133\n|road=Bullard Avenue\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=R30.45\n|exit=134\n|road=Herndon Avenue&nbsp;\u2013 [[Clovis, California|Clovis]]\n|notes=Connects to [[California State Route 99|SR 99]] north\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=R31.68\n|exit=135\n|road=Friant Road, Blackstone Avenue&nbsp;\u2013 [[Millerton Lake]]\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|county=Madera\n|cspan=5\n|county_note=MAD 0.00-45.74\n|location=none\n|postmile=R1.20\n|exit=138\n|road=Rio Mesa Boulevard, Children's Boulevard ([[California State Route 41 Business|SR 41 Bus.]] north)\n|notes=Signed as exits 138A (Rio Mesa Boulevard) and 138B (Children's Boulevard) northbound\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|location=none\n|postmile=none\n|place=North end of freeway\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|location=none\n|postmile=3.23\n|road={{jct|state=CA|SR-Bus|41|dir1=south|name1=Avenue 12|city1=Madera Ranchos}}\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|location=none\n|postmile=9.25\n|road={{jct|state=CA|SR|145|dir1=south|to2=yes|SR|99|dir2=north|road=Road 145|city1=Madera|location2=[[Millerton Lake]]}}\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|location=Oakhurst\n|postmile=35.48\n|road={{jct|state=CA|SR|49|dir1=north|city1=Ahwahnee|city2=Mariposa}}\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|county=Mariposa\n|cspan=4\n|county_note=MPA 0.00-4.92\n|location=Fish Camp\n|postmile=4.92\n|place=North end of Highway 41 at [[Yosemite National Park]] south entrance\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|location=none\n|postmile=none\n|place=[[Wawona Tunnel]]\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|location=none\n|type=incomplete\n|postmile=none\n|road={{jct|state=CA|SR|140|dir1=east}}\n|notes=Entrance only\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|location=none\n|type=incomplete\n|postmile=none\n|exit=\n|road=Southside Drive\n|notes=Continuation beyond SR 140; southbound entrance only accessible via Northside Drive to SR 140\n}}\n{{Jctbtm|col=6|keys=concur,incomplete}}\n{{reflist|group=\"N\"}}\n\n==See also==\n*{{portal-inline|California Roads}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Attached KML|display=inline,title}}\n{{Commons category|California State Route 41}}{{wikisource|Wawona Road (HAER No. CA-148) written historical and descriptive data}}\n* [http://www.aaroads.com/california/ca-041.html California @ AARoads.com - State Route 41]\n* [http://www.dot.ca.gov/hq/roadinfo/sr41 Caltrans: Route 41 highway conditions]\n* [http://www.cahighways.org/041-048.html#041 California Highways: Route 41]\n\n{{Yosemite National Park}}\n\n[[Category:State highways in California|041]]\n[[Category:Freeways in California|041]]\n[[Category:Roads in Kern County, California|State Route 041]]\n[[