ciences, Engineering and Technology Resources ]\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/2007/04/03/science/earth/03clim.html/The wind-powered desalinization plant in Perth, Australia, is an example of how technology is insulating rich countries from impacts of climate change, while poor countries remain particularly vulnerable.]\n* [http://www.desalresponsegroup.org The Desal Response Group]\n* [http://www.desware.net/ Encyclopedia of Desalination and water and Water Resources]\n* [http://www.desalination.biz/ Desalination & Water Reuse \u2013 Desalination news]\n* [http://www.ewra.net/ew/pdf/EW_2004_7-8_04.pdf Desalination: The Cyprus Experience]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120425132207/http://www.jerseywater.je/pdffiles/fact_sheets/raw_water_processing.pdf Desalination: The Jersey Water plant at La Rosi\u00e8re, Corbiere]\n* [https://fas.org/sgp/crs/misc/R40477.pdf Desalination and Membrane Technologies: Federal Research and Adoption Issues] [[Congressional Research Service]]\n* [http://topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/subjects/d/desalination/index.html?inline=nyt-classifier Desalination Articles, Commentary and Archive]: ''The New York Times''\n* [http://www.desalfacts.com/ Future Desalination Technology Database]\n\n{{Natural resources}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Environmental issues with water]]\n[[Category:Filters]]\n[[Category:Fresh water]]\n[[Category:Water supply]]\n[[Category:Water desalination]]\n[[Category:Water treatment]]\n", "name_user": "Cbrieeze", "label": "safe", "comment": "changed 'near' to 'on'", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Desalination"}
{"title_page": "Haverford College Arboretum", "text_new": "{{Infobox museum\n| name = Haverford College Arboretum\n| logo = Haverford College Arboretum Logo.png\n| image = \n| map_type = \n| map_relief = \n| former_name = \n| established = 1834\n| location = 370 Lancaster Avenue, Haverford, PA 19041 USA\n| coordinates = {{coord|40.01162|-75.29895|display=inline}}\n| type = [[Arboretum]] [[Public gardens|Public garden]]\n| founder = William Carvill\n| director = Claudia Kent\n| curator = Sally Anderson\n| owner = [[Haverford College]]\n| publictransit = [[Haverford station (NHSL)| SEPTA Norristown High Speed Line]], [[Haverford station (SEPTA Regional Rail)| SEPTA Regional Rail]]\n| website = [https://www.haverford.edu/arboretum Haverford College Arboretum]\n}}\n\nThe '''Haverford College Arboretum''' ({{convert|216|acre}}) is an [[arboretum]] comprising the entire campus of [[Haverford College]], in [[Haverford, Pennsylvania]]. It is open daily, dawn to dusk, without charge.\n\nAs of 2006, the arboretum contains mature [[oak]]s and [[maple]]s, specimen trees, flowering trees, and natural woodland areas. Over 1,500 trees are labeled with their scientific name, common name and nativity. Specific points of interest include:\n\n*Ryan [[Pinetum]] - Over 300 mature [[conifer]]s, labeled and arranged by family groupings.\n*State champion trees - Loblolly Pine, ''[[Pinus]] taeda''; and Hinoki False Cypress, ''[[Chamaecyparis]] obtusa''. \n*Penn Treaty Elm - a descendant of the [[American Elm]] under which [[William Penn]] signed his treaty with [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]]s; planted 1915. In 2010, a descendant of Haverford's Elm was planted in [[Penn Treaty Park]], the site of the 1683 treaty. \n*Asian gardens - the Denis Asian Garden and Teaf Memorial Zen-style Garden.\n*2.2-mile [https://www.haverford.edu/sites/default/files/Office/Arboretum/Haverford-Nature-Trail.pdf Nature Trail] - A public, wooded recreation trail following the perimeter of campus, popular with runners and dog walkers\n\n== History ==\nThe arboretum's origins stretch back to 1831, when the campus property was purchased by a group of Welsh Quakers. The College itself was founded two years later. \n\nIn 1834, English gardener William Carvill laid out the campus in the English landscape tradition championed by noted landscape architect Sir [[Humphry Repton]]. \n\nIn 1901, shortly after the discovery of Carvill's original landscape drawings, students and alumni seeking to preserve Haverford's natural beauty formed the Campus Club.\n\nIn 1928 the College minutes record that \"a comprehensive planting of trees\" was discussed, and in response the Superintendent of Grounds began a scientific collection of trees arranged in generic and family groupings. \n\nThe Haverford College Arboretum Association was founded in 1974 and continues to oversee the preservation of historic landscapes and trees; the implementation of sustainable plantings and practices; and the development of educational community programming. \n\n==See also==\n*[[List of botanical gardens in the United States]]\n*[[ArbNet]]\n*[http://americasgardencapital.org/ Philadelphia - America's Garden Capital]\n*[https://www.arborday.org/programs/treecampususa/index.cfm Tree Campus USA]\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/927383622|title=Haverford College arboretum|last=Van Artsdalen |first=Martha J.|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|year=2016|isbn=1467115916|location=Charleston, South Carolina|oclc=927383622}}\n[[File:The Haverford College duck pond through 3 seasons..png|thumb|624x624px|The Duck Pond through three seasons.]]\n[[File:Ryan Pinetum at Haverford College.jpg|thumb|The Ryan Pinetum and meadows at [[Haverford College]] in Spring 2017. ]]\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.haverford.edu/arboretum Haverford College Arboretum]\n*[https://www.facebook.com/HaverfordCollegeArboretum/ Facebook]\n*[https://www.instagram.com/haverfordcollegearboretum/ Instagram]\n\n[[Category:Arboreta in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Botanical gardens in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Haverford Township, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Parks in Delaware County, Pennsylvania]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox museum\n| name = Haverford College Arboretum\n| logo = Haverford College Arboretum Logo.png\n| image = \n| map_type = \n| map_relief = \n| former_name = \n| established = 1834\n| location = 370 Lancaster Avenue, Haverford, PA 19041 USA\n| coordinates = {{coord|40.01162|-75.29895|display=inline}}\n| type = [[Arboretum]] [[Public gardens|Public garden]]\n| founder = William Carvill\n| director = Claudia Kent\n| curator = Sally Anderson\n| owner = [[Haverford College]]\n| publictransit = [[Haverford station (NHSL)| SEPTA Norristown High Speed Line]], [[Haverford station| SEPTA Regional Rail]]\n| website = [https://www.haverford.edu/arboretum Haverford College Arboretum]\n}}\n\nThe '''Haverford College Arboretum''' ({{convert|216|acre}}) is an [[arboretum]] comprising the entire campus of [[Haverford College]], in [[Haverford, Pennsylvania]]. It is open daily, dawn to dusk, without charge.\n\nAs of 2006, the arboretum contains mature [[oak]]s and [[maple]]s, specimen trees, flowering trees, and natural woodland areas. Over 1,500 trees are labeled with their scientific name, common name and nativity. Specific points of interest include:\n\n*Ryan [[Pinetum]] - Over 300 mature [[conifer]]s, labeled and arranged by family groupings.\n*State champion trees - Loblolly Pine, ''[[Pinus]] taeda''; and Hinoki False Cypress, ''[[Chamaecyparis]] obtusa''. \n*Penn Treaty Elm - a descendant of the [[American Elm]] under which [[William Penn]] signed his treaty with [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]]s; planted 1915. In 2010, a descendant of Haverford's Elm was planted in [[Penn Treaty Park]], the site of the 1683 treaty. \n*Asian gardens - the Denis Asian Garden and Teaf Memorial Zen-style Garden.\n*2.2-mile [https://www.haverford.edu/sites/default/files/Office/Arboretum/Haverford-Nature-Trail.pdf Nature Trail] - A public, wooded recreation trail following the perimeter of campus, popular with runners and dog walkers\n\n== History ==\nThe arboretum's origins stretch back to 1831, when the campus property was purchased by a group of Welsh Quakers. The College itself was founded two years later. \n\nIn 1834, English gardener William Carvill laid out the campus in the English landscape tradition championed by noted landscape architect Sir [[Humphry Repton]]. \n\nIn 1901, shortly after the discovery of Carvill's original landscape drawings, students and alumni seeking to preserve Haverford's natural beauty formed the Campus Club.\n\nIn 1928 the College minutes record that \"a comprehensive planting of trees\" was discussed, and in response the Superintendent of Grounds began a scientific collection of trees arranged in generic and family groupings. \n\nThe Haverford College Arboretum Association was founded in 1974 and continues to oversee the preservation of historic landscapes and trees; the implementation of sustainable plantings and practices; and the development of educational community programming. \n\n==See also==\n*[[List of botanical gardens in the United States]]\n*[[ArbNet]]\n*[http://americasgardencapital.org/ Philadelphia - America's Garden Capital]\n*[https://www.arborday.org/programs/treecampususa/index.cfm Tree Campus USA]\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/927383622|title=Haverford College arboretum|last=Van Artsdalen |first=Martha J.|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|year=2016|isbn=1467115916|location=Charleston, South Carolina|oclc=927383622}}\n[[File:The Haverford College duck pond through 3 seasons..png|thumb|624x624px|The Duck Pond through three seasons.]]\n[[File:Ryan Pinetum at Haverford College.jpg|thumb|The Ryan Pinetum and meadows at [[Haverford College]] in Spring 2017. ]]\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.haverford.edu/arboretum Haverford College Arboretum]\n*[https://www.facebook.com/HaverfordCollegeArboretum/ Facebook]\n*[https://www.instagram.com/haverfordcollegearboretum/ Instagram]\n\n[[Category:Arboreta in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Botanical gardens in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Haverford Township, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Parks in Delaware County, Pennsylvania]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toHaverford station(link changed toHaverford station (SEPTA Regional Rail)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Haverford_College_Arboretum"}
{"title_page": "The Stand", "text_new": "{{short description|1978 novel by Stephen King}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2013}}\n{{Infobox book| <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Novels or Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books -->\n| name         = The Stand\n| title_orig   =\n| translator   =\n| image        = The Stand cover.jpg\n| caption      = First edition cover\n| author       = [[Stephen King]]\n| cover_artist = John Cayea\n| country      = United States\n| language     = English\n| series       =\n| genre        = [[Apocalyptic and post-apocalyptic fiction|Post-apocalyptic]], [[Fantasy literature|fantasy]], [[horror fiction|horror]]\n| publisher    = [[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]]\n| release_date = October 3, 1978\n| media_type   = Print ([[hardcover]] and [[paperback]])\n| pages        = 823\n| isbn         = 978-0-385-12168-2\n| preceded_by  =\n| followed_by  =\n}}\n\n'''''The Stand''''' is a [[Apocalyptic and post-apocalyptic fiction|post-apocalyptic]] [[dark fantasy]] novel written by American author [[Stephen King]] and first published in 1978 by [[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]]. The plot centers on a [[pandemic]] of a weaponized strain of [[influenza]] that kills almost the entire world population. The few survivors, united in groups, establish a new social system and engage in confrontation with each other. In writing the book, King sought to create an epic in the spirit of ''[[The Lord of the Rings]]'' that was set in contemporary America. The book was difficult for King to write because of the large number of characters and storylines.\n\nIn 1990, ''The Stand'' was reprinted as a \"Complete and Uncut\" edition. King restored some fragments of texts that were initially reduced, revised the order of the chapters, shifted the novel's setting from 1980 to ten years forward, and accordingly corrected a number of cultural references. The Complete and Uncut edition of ''The Stand'' is considered to be King's longest stand-alone work. The book has sold 4.5 million copies.\n\n''The Stand'' was highly appreciated by literary critics and is considered one of King's best novels. It received a number of literary award nominations, including the [[Balrog Award]], the [[Locus Award]] and the [[World Fantasy Award]], and was included in lists of the best books of all time by ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', the [[Modern Library]], [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] and the [[BBC]]. Reviewers praised the believability of the story, the relevance of the issues raised and the liveliness of the characters, but criticized the protractedness of individual episodes, the plot dualism and the deliberate denouement. A [[The Stand (1994 miniseries)|self-titled miniseries]] based on the novel was broadcast on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] in 1994. From 2008 to 2012, [[Marvel Comics]] published a [[The Stand (comics)|series of comics]] written by [[Roberto Aguirre-Sacasa]] and illustrated by [[Mike Perkins]]. A [[The Stand (upcoming miniseries)|miniseries]] to air on [[CBS All Access]] is in development.\n\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n==Plot==\nAn extremely contagious and lethal strain of [[influenza]], resistant to antibodies and vaccines, is developed as a [[Biological warfare|biological weapon]] within a secret [[United States Department of Defense|U.S. Department of Defense]] laboratory, and is accidentally released. The Complete and Uncut edition includes a prologue detailing the development of the virus and the security breach that causes its release. The laboratory staff die, but security guard Charles Campion manages to escape and takes his family out of state. After a couple of days, his car crashes at a gas station in Arnette, Texas. The gas station employees and ambulance workers are infected when they take the dying Campion out of his car and to a hospital. The gas station owner infects his cousin, a highway patrolman, and the virus rapidly spreads uncontrollably from there. The [[United States Army]] attempts to isolate Arnette, going as far as to execute unarmed civilians, but the efforts are in vain \u2013 the virus, christened by journalists as the \"superflu\" or \"Captain Trips\", spreads across the country and travels beyond its borders, triggering a global [[pandemic]] of apocalyptic proportions. Approximately 99.4% of the world's population is infected and killed within a month. A prism of several personal tragedies describes the collapse of society, explosions of violence, the inability of the government and [[martial law]] to stop the pandemic, and the near-extinction of humanity. Many survivors of the virus also die, unable to accept the loss of their loved ones or survive in a world where they must fend for themselves.\n\nStuart Redman, one of the gas station employees, proves immune to the virus. He is forcibly held in a specialized center in Stovington, Vermont, in the hope that a treatment can be made. Redman escapes after the center's staff dies; he is forced to kill one of the members in self-defense. He meets with sociology professor Glen Bateman, pregnant college student Frannie Goldsmith, and teenage outcast Harold Lauder. Larry Underwood, a disillusioned pop singer, joins the group in the wake of his mother's death. Stuart and Frannie are drawn to each other and become lovers, to Harold's disappointment and resentment. The group share a common dream in which they see a 108-year-old black woman living in [[Hemingford, Nebraska|Hemingford Home, Nebraska]].<ref>King used Hemingford, NE for both novels, ''The Stand'', and ''It'', America's heartland location for Mother Abigail. '''The Denver Post''', ''USA Weekend'', March 19\u201320, 2010, usaweekend.com, page 2.</ref> The woman, Abigail Freemantle \u2013 better known as \"Mother Abigail\" \u2013 becomes the group's spiritual leader. She brings the group to [[Boulder, Colorado]], to which other survivors are attracted by her telepathic appeals. New additions to the group include Nick Andros, a [[deaf-mute]] deputy from Shoyo, Arkansas; Tom Cullen, a kind-hearted, mentally challenged man from May, Oklahoma; Nadine Cross, a teacher from New Hampshire; and Ralph Brentner, a good-natured farmer from Oklahoma. The group attempts to build a new society. They call their land the \"Free Zone\", organize funeral brigades and restore a supply of electricity.\n\nMeanwhile, in [[Las Vegas Valley|Las Vegas]], [[Randall Flagg]], a \"dark man\" possessing supernatural abilities, creates his own society from people called by his visions. The people worship Flagg as a messiah and joyfully submit to his fascist dictatorship, in which drug addicts are crucified. Flagg rescues potentially cannibalistic prisoner Lloyd Henreid and makes him his right-hand man. A [[Pyromania|pyromaniac]] nicknamed \"The Trashcan Man\", after destroying oil tanks in [[Gary, Indiana]] and meeting a madman named \"The Kid\", joins Flagg's group and becomes a weapons specialist. Flagg prepares for war with Boulder. Mother Abigail, feeling that she has become prideful due to her pleasure at being a public figure, disappears into the wilderness on a journey of spiritual reconciliation. During her absence, the Free Zone's leadership committee decides to secretly send three people to Flagg's territory to act as spies. Harold and Nadine, tempted by Flagg through their dreams, stage an attack on the committee with a bomb. The explosion kills several people, but most of the committee members avoid the explosion thanks to Mother Abigail's return. Before dying of exhaustion, Mother Abigail reports God's will \u2013 Stuart, Glen, Larry and Ralph must go to Las Vegas and destroy Flagg.\n\nStuart breaks his leg en route and persuades the others to go on without him, telling them that God will provide for him if that is what is meant to happen. The remaining three are soon taken prisoner by Flagg's army. When Glen refuses to grovel before Flagg, he is killed by Lloyd. Flagg gathers his entire collective to witness the execution of Ralph and Larry. Moments before they are to be killed, the Trashcan Man arrives with a retrieved [[nuclear warhead]]. Flagg conjures a magical ball of energy in an attempt to silence a dissenter, but it is transformed into a giant glowing hand \u2014 \"The Hand of God\" \u2014 which detonates the bomb, destroying Las Vegas and killing all of Flagg's followers, in addition to Larry and Ralph. The inhabitants of Boulder anxiously await the birth of Frannie's baby. They fear that the child may not possess an immunity to the superflu and may die, implying a permanent end to humanity. Soon after she gives birth to her son, Stuart returns to Boulder, having been rescued first by a dog, Kojak, and then by Tom, the only survivor of the three Free Zone spies. The baby, Peter, manages to fight off the superflu. Stuart and Frannie decide to leave Boulder and move to [[Ogunquit]] as society is slowly reestablished. The Complete and Uncut Edition includes an [[epilogue]] in which Flagg, having survived the nuclear explosion, wakes up somewhere in the Southern Hemisphere. Regaining his former strength, he begins recruiting adherents among a preliterate, dark-skinned people.\n\n==Characters==\n{{Main|List of The Stand characters}}\n\n== Background ==\nIn [[Danse Macabre (book)|''Danse Macabre'']], King writes about the origins of ''The Stand'' at some length. One source was [[Patty Hearst]]'s case. The original idea was to create a novel about the episode because \"it seemed that only a novel might really succeed in explaining all the contradictions\".\n\nThe author also mentions [[George R. Stewart]]'s novel ''[[Earth Abides]]'', which describes the odyssey of one of the last human survivors after the population is nearly annihilated by a plague, as one of the main inspirations:\n\n<blockquote>\nWith my Patty Hearst book, I never found the right way in... and during that entire six-week period, something else was nagging very quietly at the back of my mind. It was a news story I had read about an accidental CBW spill in Utah. (...) This article called up memories of a novel called ''Earth Abides'', by George R. Stewart.\n</blockquote>\n\n<blockquote>\n(...) and one day while sitting at my typewriter, (...) I wrote\u2014just to write something: The world comes to an end but everybody in the SLA is somehow immune. Snake bit them. I looked at that for a while and then typed: No more gas shortages. That was sort of cheerful, in a horrible sort of way.\n<ref>{{Cite book\n  | last = King\n  | first = Stephen\n  | authorlink = Stephen King\n  | title = Stephen King's Danse Macabre\n  | publisher = Berkeley Trade\n  | page = 370\n  | isbn = 0-425-18160-X }}</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\n''The Stand'' was also planned by King as an epic ''[[The Lord of the Rings]]''\u2013type story in a contemporary American setting:\n\n<blockquote>For a long time\u2014ten years, at least\u2014I had wanted to write a fantasy epic like ''[[The Lord of the Rings]]'', only with an American setting. I just couldn't figure out how to do it. Then . . . after my wife and kids and I moved to Boulder, Colorado, I saw a ''[[60 Minutes]]'' segment on CBW (chemical-biological warfare). I never forgot the gruesome footage of the test mice shuddering, convulsing, and dying, all in twenty seconds or less. That got me remembering a chemical spill in Utah, that [[Dugway sheep incident|killed a bunch of sheep]] (these were canisters on their way to some burial ground; they fell off the truck and ruptured). I remembered a news reporter saying, 'If the winds had been blowing the other way, there was [[Salt Lake City]].' This incident later served as the basis of a movie called ''[[Rage (1972 film)|Rage]]'', starring [[George C. Scott]], but before it was released, I was deep into ''The Stand'', finally writing my American fantasy epic, set in a plague-decimated USA. Only instead of a hobbit, my hero was a Texan named Stu Redman, and instead of a Dark Lord, my villain was a ruthless drifter and supernatural madman named [[Randall Flagg]]. The land of [[Mordor]] ('where the shadows lie,' according to [[Tolkien]]) was played by Las Vegas.<ref>{{cite web\n  | last = King\n  | first = Stephen\n  | title = ''Stand: The Complete and Uncut Edition'': The Inspiration\n  | url=http://www.stephenking.com/library/novel/stand:_the_complete__uncut_edition_the_inspiration.html\n  | accessdate = 2008-08-24 }}</ref></blockquote>\n\nWhile writing ''The Stand'', King nearly stopped because of [[writer's block]].<ref>''On Writing'', Stephen King, 2000.</ref> Eventually, he reached the conclusion that the heroes were becoming too complacent, and were beginning to repeat all the same mistakes of their old society. In an attempt to resolve this, he added the part of the storyline where Harold and Nadine construct a bomb, which explodes in a Free Zone committee meeting, killing Nick Andros, Chad Norris, and Susan Stern. Later, Mother Abagail explains on her deathbed that God permitted the bombing because He was dissatisfied with the heroes' focus on petty politics, and not on the ultimate quest of destroying Flagg. When telling this story, King sardonically observed that the bomb saved the book, and that he only had to kill half of the core cast to do this.\n\n== Publication history ==\n\nThe novel was originally published in 1978 in hardcover, with a setting date of 1980, in abridged form. The first paperback release in 1980 changed the setting date to 1985. The novel marks the first appearance of [[Randall Flagg]], King's recurring antagonist, whom King would bring back many times in his later writings.\n\n{{Infobox book|\n| name         = The Stand: The Complete and Uncut Edition\n| title_orig   =\n| translator   =\n| image        = The Stand Uncut.jpg\n| caption = The Complete and Uncut Edition cover\n| author       = [[Stephen King]]\n| cover_artist = John Cayea\n| country      = US\n| language     = English\n| series       =\n| genre        = [[Postapocalyptic]]\n| publisher    = [[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]]\n| release_date = May 1990\n| media_type   = Print\n| pages        = 1,152\n| isbn         = 978-0-385-19957-5\n| preceded_by  =\n| followed_by  =\n}}\n\nIn 1990, an unabridged edition of ''The Stand'' was published, billed as \"The Complete and Uncut Edition\". Published in hardcover by Doubleday in May 1990, this became the longest book published by King at 1152 pages. When the novel was originally published in 1978, Doubleday warned King that the book's size would make it too expensive for the market to bear.<ref>{{cite book |last= King |first= Stephen |date= 1990 |title= The Stand: The Complete And Uncut Edition |publisher= [[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]] |page= xiii |isbn=978-0-307-74368-8 }}</ref> As a result, he cut about 400 pages (around 150,000 words) from the original manuscript. This edition reinstates most of the deleted pages (as selected by King), as well as updates the setting from the 1980s to the 1990s. This new edition features a new preface by King, and illustrations by [[Bernie Wrightson]]. Additionally, Doubleday published a deluxe edition of ''The Stand: The Complete & Uncut Edition'', limited to 1,250 numbered copies and 52 lettered copies. This edition, known as the \"Coffin Box\" edition due to the book being housed in a wooden case, was signed by King and Wrightson.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/97/03/09/lifetimes/king-stand.html |title=ARMAGEDDON, COMPLETE AND UNCUT|date=1997-03-09| work=The New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.veryfinebooks.com/Stephen_King_The_Stand_Signed_First_Edition_p/sk200.htm |title=Stephen King The Stand Signed Limited Coffin Edition |publisher=VeryFineBooks.com |accessdate=2012-07-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedarktower.org/palaver/showwiki.php?title=Stand+The+-+S+L |title=Stand, The \u2013 S/L \u2013 Palaver |publisher=Thedarktower.org |accessdate=2012-07-02}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n\n''The Stand'' was nominated for the [[World Fantasy Award for Best Novel]] in 1979, and was adapted into both a [[The Stand (1994 miniseries)|television miniseries]] for ABC and a [[The Stand (comics)|graphic novel]] published by [[Marvel Comics]].<ref name=\"rama1\"/><ref name=\"WWE-1979\">{{cite web\n| url = http://www.worldswithoutend.com/books_year_index.asp?year=1979\n| title = 1979 Award Winners & Nominees\n| work = Worlds Without End\n| accessdate=2009-07-22\n}}</ref> In 2003, the novel was listed at number 53 on the [[BBC]]'s [[The Big Read]] poll.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/arts/bigread/top100_2.shtml|title=The Big Read \u2013 Top 100 Books |date=April 2003 |access-date=October 3, 2017 |publisher=[[BBC]] }}</ref>\n\n==Adaptations==\n\n=== Television ===\n{{Main|The Stand (1994 miniseries)|The Stand (upcoming miniseries)}}\n\nA movie adaptation of ''The Stand'' was in [[development hell]] for over 10 years. During the 1980s, Stephen King had planned a theatrical film, with [[George A. Romero]] directing and himself writing, not trusting anybody else with the project. However, writing a workable screenplay proved difficult, due to the novel's length. King talked about adapting it for television, but was informed that the television networks did not \"want to see the end of the world, particularly in prime time.\" Eventually King allowed screenwriter [[Rospo Pallenberg]], who was a fan of ''The Stand'', to write his own adaptation of the novel. Pallenberg's script would clock the film in at close to three hours, while still staying true to the novel. Everyone liked the script; however, just as it was about to finally come together, [[Warner Bros.]] backed out of the project.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.subcin.com/risefallstand.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20060708173256/http://www.subcin.com/risefallstand.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 8, 2006 |title=THE RISE AND FALL OF \"THE STAND\" |publisher=subcin.com |author=Hixx, Don Alex |accessdate=2013-04-18 |df=mdy-all }}{{Unreliable source?|date=August 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] eventually offered Stephen King the chance to make ''The Stand'' into an eight-hour [[television miniseries|miniseries]]. King wrote a new screenplay (toned down slightly for television). The [[The Stand (1994 miniseries)|miniseries]] was broadcast in 1994, directed by [[Mick Garris]], and starred such actors as [[Gary Sinise]], Adam Storke, [[Molly Ringwald]], [[Rob Lowe]], [[Miguel Ferrer]], [[Laura San Giacomo]], [[Jamey Sheridan]], [[Ossie Davis]], [[Ruby Dee]], [[Bill Fagerbakke]], and [[Shawnee Smith]], with notable cameos including [[John Landis]], [[Ed Harris]], [[Kathy Bates]], [[Sam Raimi]], and King himself. Parts of the miniseries were shot in [[Salt Lake City]], [[Utah State Prison]], [[Sundance Resort|Sundance]], [[Orem]], [[Provo Canyon]], and [[Salina, Utah|Salina]] in [[Utah]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=D'Arc|first1=James V.|title=When Hollywood came to town: a history of moviemaking in Utah|date=2010|publisher=Gibbs Smith|location=Layton, Utah|isbn=9781423605874|edition=1st}}</ref>\n\nBetween 2011 and 2016, [[Warner Bros. Pictures]] and [[CBS Films]] were developing a feature-length film adaptation of ''The Stand''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/blogs/heat-vision/stephen-kings-stand-heading-big-94805|title=Stephen King's 'The Stand' Heading to the Big Screen (Exclusive) | work=The Hollywood Reporter | first=Borys|last=Kit|date=2011-01-31|accessdate=2014-08-02}}</ref> In August 2011, director [[David Yates]] and screenwriter [[Steve Kloves]], known for their collaboration on the ''[[Harry Potter (film series)|Harry Potter]]'' films, were hired to direct/write a multimovie version of ''The Stand'',<ref>{{cite web|last=McWeeny |first=Drew |url=http://www.hitfix.com/blogs/motion-captured/posts/exclusive-potter-masterminds-steve-kloves-and-david-yates-reunite-for-the-stand |title=Exclusive: Potter masterminds Steve Kloves and David Yates reunite for The Stand |publisher=Hitfix.com |date=2012-06-28 |accessdate=2012-07-02}}</ref> but left the project in October 2011, as Yates felt it would work better as a miniseries.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://whatculture.com/film/david-yates-says-hes-not-making-the-stand-because-it-should-be-tv-mini-series.php |title=David Yates Says He\u2019s Not Making THE STAND Because It Should Be TV Mini-Series |publisher=Whatculture.com |date=2011-11-12 |accessdate=2012-07-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120117171113/http://whatculture.com/film/david-yates-says-hes-not-making-the-stand-because-it-should-be-tv-mini-series.php |archivedate=January 17, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Both [[Ben Affleck]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Thompson|first=Anne|title=More Details on Ben Affleck in Snyder's Superman/Batman UPDATED|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/thompsononhollywood/be-affleck-is-the-new-batman-in-snyders-superman-batman|publisher=IndieWire|accessdate=2014-08-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203031502/http://blogs.indiewire.com/thompsononhollywood/be-affleck-is-the-new-batman-in-snyders-superman-batman|archive-date=December 3, 2013|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and [[Scott Cooper (director)|Scott Cooper]] dropped out over creative differences with the studio.<ref>{{cite web|last=Shaw|first=Lucas|title=\u2018Crazy Heart\u2019 Director Scott Cooper Exits Warner Bros.\u2019 Stephen King Adaptation (Exclusive)|url=http://www.thewrap.com/crazy-heart-director-scott-cooper-stephen-king|publisher=The Wrap|accessdate=2014-08-02}}</ref> On February 25, 2014, [[Josh Boone (director)|Josh Boone]] was hired to write and direct the adaptation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/fault-stars-director-talks-tackle-682033||title='Fault In Our Stars' Director in Talks to Tackle Stephen King's 'The Stand'|last=Kit|first=Borys|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=2014-02-25|accessdate=2014-09-10}}</ref> He later revealed that he wanted [[Christian Bale]] to play Randall Flagg and [[Matthew McConaughey]] for the role of Stu Redman.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/JoshBooneMovies/status/503313944413761536|title=I have always wanted McConaughey as Stu and Bale as Flagg. Still not sure how that story leaked \u2013 just not true.|author=Josh Boone|date=23 Aug 2014|publisher=Twitter}}</ref> By September 10, 2014, the script had been completed and pre-production was underway.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://collider.com/the-stand-movie-details-three-hour-cut-josh-boone/|title=Director Josh Boone On THE STAND, Fidelity to the Novel, Script Status, and Whether He'll Direct LESTAT|last=Cook|first=Tommy|work=Collider.com|date=2014-09-10|accessdate=2014-09-10}}/</ref> In November, Boone planned to split his adaptation into four full-length feature films in an effort to remain true to the breadth of King's sprawling novel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://smodcast.com/episodes/hollywood-babble-on-bonus-babble-on-hollywood-josh-boone-the-fault-in-our-stand/|title=Hollywood Babble-On Bonus: Babble on Hollywood: Josh Boone: The Fault In Our Stand|author=|date=|work=smodcast.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141120170433/http://smodcast.com/episodes/hollywood-babble-on-bonus-babble-on-hollywood-josh-boone-the-fault-in-our-stand|archivedate=November 20, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>Fleming Jr., Mike (November 21, 2014). [https://web.archive.org/web/20160221020603/http://deadline.com/2014/11/the-stand-stephen-king-josh-boone-four-films-1201291709/ \"Josh Boone Says Warner Bros Will Turn Stephen King\u2019s \u2018The Stand\u2019 Into Four Films.\"] ''Deadline''.</ref> In June 2015, Warner Bros. proposed an eight-part [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] miniseries to set up the story, which would culminate in Josh Boone's film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/447603-stephen-kings-the-stand-to-begin-as-eight-part-television-miniseries|title=Stephen King's The Stand to Begin as an Eight-Part Television Miniseries! - ComingSoon.net|date=June 5, 2015|work=comingsoon.net|accessdate=February 6, 2017}}</ref> However, in February 2016, ''The Stand'' project was put on hold and the rights reverted to CBS Films.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2016/02/josh-boone-stephen-king-revival-the-stand-the-fault-in-our-stars-1201694681/|title=\u2018The Fault In Our Stars\u2019 Helmer Josh Boone Pushes Back Stephen King\u2019s \u2018The Stand\u2019 To Next Direct \u2018Revival\u2019|last=|first=|date=February 2016|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, King talked of doing an extended TV series on Showtime or [[CBS All Access]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vulture.com/2017/09/stephen-king-on-movies-geralds-game-1922-it-the-stand.html|title=Stephen King on His New Netflix Movies, It, and His Big Year|last=Buchanan|first=Kyle|work=[[Vulture.com]]|date=September 25, 2017|accessdate=September 29, 2017}}</ref> In January 2019, a 10-hour limited series was ordered by CBS Television Studios to be broadcast on CBS All Access.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/stephen-king-stand-series-order-cbs-1203123968/|title=Stephen King\u2019s \u2018The Stand\u2019 Gets Series Order at CBS All Access|last=Low|first=Elaine|work=[[Variety.com]]|date=January 30, 2019|accessdate=January 30, 2019}}</ref> [[James Marsden]], [[Amber Heard]], [[Whoopi Goldberg]], [[Greg Kinnear]], [[Odessa Young]], and [[Henry Zaga]] were all in consideration for the roles of Stu Redman, Nadine Cross, Mother Abagail, Glen Bateman, Frannie Goldsmith, and Nick Andros, respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbr.com/stephen-kings-the-stand-casting-rumors/|title=Stephen King's The Stand TV Adaptation Reportedly Eyeing Some Huge Stars|last=Solis|first=Jorge|work=[[cbr.com]]|date=June 22, 2019|accessdate=June 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Comics===\n{{Main|The Stand (comics)}}\n[[Marvel Comics]] adapted ''The Stand'' into a series of six five-issue comic book [[Limited series (comics)|miniseries]].<ref name=\"rama1\">[http://forum.newsarama.com/showthread.php?t=150380 King: Marvel to Adapt The Stand as a graphic novel]{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, [[Newsarama]], March 17, 2008</ref> The series was written by [[Roberto Aguirre-Sacasa]] and illustrated by [[Mike Perkins]]. Colorist [[Laura Martin]], letterer [[Chris Eliopoulos]], and cover artist [[Lee Bermejo]] were also on the staff. The first issue of ''[[The Stand: Captain Trips]]'' was released on September 10, 2008.<ref name=\"MarvelAnnounces\">{{cite web |url=http://marvel.com/news/comicstories.3768.WW_Philly_2008%7Ecolon%7E_The_Stand |title=Wizard World Philadelphia 2008: Stephen King's The Stand |author=Stevens, Tim |date=2008-05-31 |publisher=Marvel.com |accessdate=2014-08-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100818014514/http://marvel.com/news/comicstories.3768.WW_Philly_2008~colon~_The_Stand |archive-date=August 18, 2010 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Music===\n[[Metallica]] derived the title for its song \"Ride the Lightning\" from a quote from ''The Stand''.<ref name=\"HowWeMade\">{{cite web |url=https://www.loudersound.com/features/metallica-how-we-made-ride-the-lightning |title=How We Made Ride the Lightning |author=Everley, Dave |date=2016-05-19 |publisher=loudersound.com |accessdate=2019-06-03|df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n[[The Alarm]]  had a song on the album [[Declaration (The Alarm album)|Declaration]]  called \"The Stand (Prophecy)\" as an homage to the book. The song contained certain lyrics directly related to the book, such as \"I met the walking dude, religious, with his worn out cowboy boots,\" and \"Hey Trashcan where you going boy?\"   \nThe main chorus of the song was \"Come on down and meet your maker, come on down and make the stand.\"{{cn}}\n\nThe title track to the album ''[[Among the Living]]'' by the band [[Anthrax (American band)|Anthrax]] is based on the novel.{{cn}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{isfdb title|id=1148|title=The Stand}}\n* [http://www.bookpoi.com/the_stand_by_stephen_king_first_edition_identification.html Bookpoi]\u2014How to identify first edition copies of ''The Stand'' by Stephen King.\n\n{{The Stand}}\n{{Stephen King}}\n{{DarkTower}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stand, The}}\n[[Category:The Stand]]\n[[Category:1978 American novels]]\n[[Category:American post-apocalyptic novels]]\n[[Category:American horror novels]]\n[[Category:Biological weapons in popular culture]]\n[[Category:Novels about dreams]]\n[[Category:Novels about nightmares]]\n[[Category:Novels about religion]]\n[[Category:Fictional events]]\n[[Category:Novels by Stephen King]]\n[[Category:Novels set in the 1980s]]\n[[Category:Novels set in the 1990s]]\n[[Category:Novels set in Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Novels set in Atlanta]]\n[[Category:Novels set in Boulder, Colorado]]\n[[Category:Novels set in Indiana]]\n[[Category:Novels set in the Las Vegas Valley]]\n[[Category:Novels set in Maine]]\n[[Category:Novels set in Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Novels set in New York City]]\n[[Category:Novels set in New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Novels set in Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Novels set in Texas]]\n[[Category:Novels set in Vermont]]\n[[Category:Novels about viral outbreaks]]\n[[Category:Doubleday (publisher) books]]\n[[Category:Novels adapted into television programs]]\n[[Category:Demon novels]]\n[[Category:Novels adapted into comics]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1978 novel by Stephen King}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2013}}\n{{Infobox book| <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Novels or Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books -->\n| name         = The Stand\n| title_orig   =\n| translator   =\n| image        = The Stand cover.jpg\n| caption      = First edition cover\n| author       = [[Stephen King]]\n| cover_artist = John Cayea\n| country      = United States\n| language     = English\n| series       =\n| genre        = [[Apocalyptic and post-apocalyptic fiction|Post-apocalyptic]], [[Fantasy literature|fantasy]], [[horror fiction|horror]]\n| publisher    = [[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]]\n| release_date = October 3, 1978\n| media_type   = Print ([[hardcover]] and [[paperback]])\n| pages        = 823\n| isbn         = 978-0-385-12168-2\n| preceded_by  =\n| followed_by  =\n}}\n\n'''''The Stand''''' is a [[Apocalyptic and post-apocalyptic fiction|post-apocalyptic]] [[dark fantasy]] novel written by American author [[Stephen King]] and first published in 1978 by [[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]]. The plot centers on a [[pandemic]] of a weaponized strain of [[influenza]] that kills almost the entire world population. The few survivors, united in groups, establish a new social system and engage in confrontation with each other. In writing the book, King sought to create an epic in the spirit of ''[[The Lord of the Rings]]'' that was set in contemporary America. The book was difficult for King to write because of the large number of characters and storylines.\n\nIn 1990, ''The Stand'' was reprinted as a \"Complete and Uncut\" edition. King restored some fragments of texts that were initially reduced, revised the order of the chapters, shifted the novel's setting from 1980 to ten years forward, and accordingly corrected a number of cultural references. The Complete and Uncut edition of ''The Stand'' is considered to be King's longest stand-alone work. The book has sold 4.5 million copies.\n\n''The Stand'' was highly appreciated by literary critics and is considered one of King's best novels. It received a number of literary award nominations, including the [[Balrog Award]], the [[Locus Award]] and the [[World Fantasy Award]], and was included in lists of the best books of all time by ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', the [[Modern Library]], [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] and the [[BBC]]. Reviewers praised the believability of the story, the relevance of the issues raised and the liveliness of the characters, but criticized the protractedness of individual episodes, the plot dualism and the deliberate denouement. A [[The Stand (1994 miniseries)|self-titled miniseries]] based on the novel was broadcast on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] in 1994. From 2008 to 2012, [[Marvel Comics]] published a [[The Stand (comics)|series of comics]] written by [[Roberto Aguirre-Sacasa]] and illustrated by [[Mike Perkins]]. A [[The Stand (upcoming miniseries)|miniseries]] to air on [[CBS All Access]] is in development.\n\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n==Plot==\nAn extremely contagious and lethal strain of [[influenza]], resistant to antibodies and vaccines, is developed as a [[Biological warfare|biological weapon]] within a secret [[United States Department of Defense|U.S. Department of Defense]] laboratory, and is accidentally released. The Complete and Uncut edition includes a prologue detailing the development of the virus and the security breach that causes its release. The laboratory staff die, but security guard Charles Campion manages to escape and takes his family out of state. After a couple of days, his car crashes at a gas station in Arnette, Texas. The gas station employees and ambulance workers are infected when they take the dying Campion out of his car and to a hospital. The gas station owner infects his cousin, a highway patrolman, and the virus rapidly spreads uncontrollably from there. The [[United States Army]] attempts to isolate Arnette, going as far as to execute unarmed civilians, but the efforts are in vain \u2013 the virus, christened by journalists as the \"superflu\" or \"Captain Trips\", spreads across the country and travels beyond its borders, triggering a global [[pandemic]] of apocalyptic proportions. Approximately 99.4% of the world's population is infected and killed within a month. A prism of several personal tragedies describes the collapse of society, explosions of violence, the inability of the government and [[martial law]] to stop the pandemic, and the near-extinction of humanity. Many survivors of the virus also die, unable to accept the loss of their loved ones or survive in a world where they must fend for themselves.\n\nStuart Redman, one of the gas station employees, proves immune to the virus. He is forcibly held in a specialized center in Stovington, Vermont, in the hope that a treatment can be made. Redman escapes after the center's staff dies; he is forced to kill one of the members in self-defense. He meets with sociology professor Glen Bateman, pregnant college student Frannie Goldsmith, and teenage outcast Harold Lauder. Larry Underwood, a disillusioned pop singer, joins the group in the wake of his mother's death. Stuart and Frannie are drawn to each other and become lovers, to Harold's disappointment and resentment. The group share a common dream in which they see a 108-year-old black woman living in [[Hemingford, Nebraska|Hemingford Home, Nebraska]].<ref>King used Hemingford, NE for both novels, ''The Stand'', and ''It'', America's heartland location for Mother Abigail. '''The Denver Post''', ''USA Weekend'', March 19\u201320, 2010, usaweekend.com, page 2.</ref> The woman, Abigail Freemantle \u2013 better known as \"Mother Abigail\" \u2013 becomes the group's spiritual leader. She brings the group to [[Boulder, Colorado]], to which other survivors are attracted by her telepathic appeals. New additions to the group include Nick Andros, a [[deaf-mute]] deputy from Shoyo, Arkansas; Tom Cullen, a kind-hearted, mentally challenged man from May, Oklahoma; Nadine Cross, a teacher from New Hampshire; and Ralph Brentner, a good-natured farmer from Oklahoma. The group attempts to build a new society. They call their land the \"Free Zone\", organize funeral brigades and restore a supply of electricity.\n\nMeanwhile, in [[Las Vegas Valley|Las Vegas]], [[Randall Flagg]], a \"dark man\" possessing supernatural abilities, creates his own society from people called by his visions. The people worship Flagg as a messiah and joyfully submit to his fascist dictatorship, in which drug addicts are crucified. Flagg rescues potentially cannibalistic prisoner Lloyd Henreid and makes him his right-hand man. A [[Pyromania|pyromaniac]] nicknamed \"The Trashcan Man\", after destroying oil tanks in [[Gary, Indiana]] and meeting a madman named \"The Kid\", joins Flagg's group and becomes a weapons specialist. Flagg prepares for war with Boulder. Mother Abigail, feeling that she has become prideful due to her pleasure at being a public figure, disappears into the wilderness on a journey of spiritual reconciliation. During her absence, the Free Zone's leadership committee decides to secretly send three people to Flagg's territory to act as spies. Harold and Nadine, tempted by Flagg through their dreams, stage an attack on the committee with a bomb. The explosion kills several people, but most of the committee members avoid the explosion thanks to Mother Abigail's return. Before dying of exhaustion, Mother Abigail reports God's will \u2013 Stuart, Glen, Larry and Ralph must go to Las Vegas and destroy Flagg.\n\nStuart breaks his leg en route and persuades the others to go on without him, telling them that God will provide for him if that is what is meant to happen. The remaining three are soon taken prisoner by Flagg's army. When Glen refuses to grovel before Flagg, he is killed by Lloyd. Flagg gathers his entire collective to witness the execution of Ralph and Larry. Moments before they are to be killed, the Trashcan Man arrives with a retrieved [[nuclear warhead]]. Flagg conjures a magical ball of energy in an attempt to silence a dissenter, but it is transformed into a giant glowing hand \u2014 \"The Hand of God\" \u2014 which detonates the bomb, destroying Las Vegas and killing all of Flagg's followers, in addition to Larry and Ralph. The inhabitants of Boulder anxiously await the birth of Frannie's baby. They fear that the child may not possess an immunity to the superflu and may die, implying a permanent end to humanity. Soon after she gives birth to her son, Stuart returns to Boulder, having been rescued first by a dog, Kojak, and then by Tom, the only survivor of the three Free Zone spies. The baby, Peter, manages to fight off the superflu. Stuart and Frannie decide to leave Boulder and move to [[Ogunquit]] as society is slowly reestablished. The Complete and Uncut Edition includes an [[epilogue]] in which Flagg, having survived the nuclear explosion, wakes up somewhere in the Southern Hemisphere. Regaining his former strength, he begins recruiting adherents among a preliterate, dark-skinned people.\n\n==Characters==\n{{Main|List of The Stand characters}}\n\n== Background ==\nIn [[Danse Macabre (book)|''Danse Macabre'']], King writes about the origins of ''The Stand'' at some length. One source was [[Patty Hearst]]'s case. The original idea was to create a novel about the episode because \"it seemed that only a novel might really succeed in explaining all the contradictions\".\n\nThe author also mentions [[George R. Stewart]]'s novel ''[[Earth Abides]]'', which describes the odyssey of one of the last human survivors after the population is nearly annihilated by a plague, as one of the main inspirations:\n\n<blockquote>\nWith my Patty Hearst book, I never found the right way in... and during that entire six-week period, something else was nagging very quietly at the back of my mind. It was a news story I had read about an accidental CBW spill in Utah. (...) This article called up memories of a novel called ''Earth Abides'', by George R. Stewart.\n</blockquote>\n\n<blockquote>\n(...) and one day while sitting at my typewriter, (...) I wrote\u2014just to write something: The world comes to an end but everybody in the SLA is somehow immune. Snake bit them. I looked at that for a while and then typed: No more gas shortages. That was sort of cheerful, in a horrible sort of way.\n<ref>{{Cite book\n  | last = King\n  | first = Stephen\n  | authorlink = Stephen King\n  | title = Stephen King's Danse Macabre\n  | publisher = Berkeley Trade\n  | page = 370\n  | isbn = 0-425-18160-X }}</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\n''The Stand'' was also planned by King as an epic ''[[The Lord of the Rings]]''\u2013type story in a contemporary American setting:\n\n<blockquote>For a long time\u2014ten years, at least\u2014I had wanted to write a fantasy epic like ''[[The Lord of the Rings]]'', only with an American setting. I just couldn't figure out how to do it. Then . . . after my wife and kids and I moved to Boulder, Colorado, I saw a ''[[60 Minutes]]'' segment on CBW (chemical-biological warfare). I never forgot the gruesome footage of the test mice shuddering, convulsing, and dying, all in twenty seconds or less. That got me remembering a chemical spill in Utah, that [[Dugway sheep incident|killed a bunch of sheep]] (these were canisters on their way to some burial ground; they fell off the truck and ruptured). I remembered a news reporter saying, 'If the winds had been blowing the other way, there was [[Salt Lake City]].' This incident later served as the basis of a movie called ''[[Rage (1972 film)|Rage]]'', starring [[George C. Scott]], but before it was released, I was deep into ''The Stand'', finally writing my American fantasy epic, set in a plague-decimated USA. Only instead of a hobbit, my hero was a Texan named Stu Redman, and instead of a Dark Lord, my villain was a ruthless drifter and supernatural madman named [[Randall Flagg]]. The land of [[Mordor]] ('where the shadows lie,' according to [[Tolkien]]) was played by Las Vegas.<ref>{{cite web\n  | last = King\n  | first = Stephen\n  | title = ''Stand: The Complete and Uncut Edition'': The Inspiration\n  | url=http://www.stephenking.com/library/novel/stand:_the_complete__uncut_edition_the_inspiration.html\n  | accessdate = 2008-08-24 }}</ref></blockquote>\n\nWhile writing ''The Stand'', King nearly stopped because of [[writer's block]].<ref>''On Writing'', Stephen King, 2000.</ref> Eventually, he reached the conclusion that the heroes were becoming too complacent, and were beginning to repeat all the same mistakes of their old society. In an attempt to resolve this, he added the part of the storyline where Harold and Nadine construct a bomb, which explodes in a Free Zone committee meeting, killing Nick Andros, Chad Norris, and Susan Stern. Later, Mother Abagail explains on her deathbed that God permitted the bombing because He was dissatisfied with the heroes' focus on petty politics, and not on the ultimate quest of destroying Flagg. When telling this story, King sardonically observed that the bomb saved the book, and that he only had to kill half of the core cast to do this.\n\n== Publication history ==\n\nThe novel was originally published in 1978 in hardcover, with a setting date of 1980, in abridged form. The first paperback release in 1980 changed the setting date to 1985. The novel marks the first appearance of [[Randall Flagg]], King's recurring antagonist, whom King would bring back many times in his later writings.\n\n{{Infobox book|\n| name         = The Stand: The Complete and Uncut Edition\n| title_orig   =\n| translator   =\n| image        = The Stand Uncut.jpg\n| caption = The Complete and Uncut Edition cover\n| author       = [[Stephen King]]\n| cover_artist = John Cayea\n| country      = US\n| language     = English\n| series       =\n| genre        = [[Postapocalyptic]]\n| publisher    = [[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]]\n| release_date = May 1990\n| media_type   = Print\n| pages        = 1,152\n| isbn         = 978-0-385-19957-5\n| preceded_by  =\n| followed_by  =\n}}\n\nIn 1990, an unabridged edition of ''The Stand'' was published, billed as \"The Complete and Uncut Edition\". Published in hardcover by Doubleday in May 1990, this became the longest book published by King at 1152 pages. When the novel was originally published in 1978, Doubleday warned King that the book's size would make it too expensive for the market to bear.<ref>{{cite book |last= King |first= Stephen |date= 1990 |title= The Stand: The Complete And Uncut Edition |publisher= [[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]] |page= xiii |isbn=978-0-307-74368-8 }}</ref> As a result, he cut about 400 pages (around 150,000 words) from the original manuscript. This edition reinstates most of the deleted pages (as selected by King), as well as updates the setting from the 1980s to the 1990s. This new edition features a new preface by King, and illustrations by [[Bernie Wrightson]]. Additionally, Doubleday published a deluxe edition of ''The Stand: The Complete & Uncut Edition'', limited to 1,250 numbered copies and 52 lettered copies. This edition, known as the \"Coffin Box\" edition due to the book being housed in a wooden case, was signed by King and Wrightson.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/97/03/09/lifetimes/king-stand.html |title=ARMAGEDDON, COMPLETE AND UNCUT|date=1997-03-09| work=The New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.veryfinebooks.com/Stephen_King_The_Stand_Signed_First_Edition_p/sk200.htm |title=Stephen King The Stand Signed Limited Coffin Edition |publisher=VeryFineBooks.com |accessdate=2012-07-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedarktower.org/palaver/showwiki.php?title=Stand+The+-+S+L |title=Stand, The \u2013 S/L \u2013 Palaver |publisher=Thedarktower.org |accessdate=2012-07-02}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n\n''The Stand'' was nominated for the [[World Fantasy Award for Best Novel]] in 1979, and was adapted into both a [[The Stand (1994 miniseries)|television miniseries]] for ABC and a [[The Stand (comics)|graphic novel]] published by [[Marvel Comics]].<ref name=\"rama1\"/><ref name=\"WWE-1979\">{{cite web\n| url = http://www.worldswithoutend.com/books_year_index.asp?year=1979\n| title = 1979 Award Winners & Nominees\n| work = Worlds Without End\n| accessdate=2009-07-22\n}}</ref> In 2003, the novel was listed at number 53 on the [[BBC]]'s [[The Big Read]] poll.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/arts/bigread/top100_2.shtml|title=The Big Read \u2013 Top 100 Books |date=April 2003 |access-date=October 3, 2017 |publisher=[[BBC]] }}</ref>\n\n==Adaptations==\n\n=== Television ===\n{{Main|The Stand (1994 miniseries)|The Stand (upcoming miniseries)}}\n\nA movie adaptation of ''The Stand'' was in [[development hell]] for over 10 years. During the 1980s, Stephen King had planned a theatrical film, with [[George A. Romero]] directing and himself writing, not trusting anybody else with the project. However, writing a workable screenplay proved difficult, due to the novel's length. King talked about adapting it for television, but was informed that the television networks did not \"want to see the end of the world, particularly in prime time.\" Eventually King allowed screenwriter [[Rospo Pallenberg]], who was a fan of ''The Stand'', to write his own adaptation of the novel. Pallenberg's script would clock the film in at close to three hours, while still staying true to the novel. Everyone liked the script; however, just as it was about to finally come together, [[Warner Bros.]] backed out of the project.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.subcin.com/risefallstand.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20060708173256/http://www.subcin.com/risefallstand.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 8, 2006 |title=THE RISE AND FALL OF \"THE STAND\" |publisher=subcin.com |author=Hixx, Don Alex |accessdate=2013-04-18 |df=mdy-all }}{{Unreliable source?|date=August 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] eventually offered Stephen King the chance to make ''The Stand'' into an eight-hour [[television miniseries|miniseries]]. King wrote a new screenplay (toned down slightly for television). The [[The Stand (1994 miniseries)|miniseries]] was broadcast in 1994, directed by [[Mick Garris]], and starred such actors as [[Gary Sinise]], Adam Storke, [[Molly Ringwald]], [[Rob Lowe]], [[Miguel Ferrer]], [[Laura San Giacomo]], [[Jamey Sheridan]], [[Ossie Davis]], [[Ruby Dee]], [[Bill Fagerbakke]], and [[Shawnee Smith]], with notable cameos including [[John Landis]], [[Ed Harris]], [[Kathy Bates]], [[Sam Raimi]], and King himself. Parts of the miniseries were shot in [[Salt Lake City]], [[Utah State Prison]], [[Sundance Resort|Sundance]], [[Orem]], [[Provo Canyon]], and [[Salina, Utah|Salina]] in [[Utah]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=D'Arc|first1=James V.|title=When Hollywood came to town: a history of moviemaking in Utah|date=2010|publisher=Gibbs Smith|location=Layton, Utah|isbn=9781423605874|edition=1st}}</ref>\n\nBetween 2011 and 2016, [[Warner Bros. Pictures]] and [[CBS Films]] were developing a feature-length film adaptation of ''The Stand''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/blogs/heat-vision/stephen-kings-stand-heading-big-94805|title=Stephen King's 'The Stand' Heading to the Big Screen (Exclusive) | work=The Hollywood Reporter | first=Borys|last=Kit|date=2011-01-31|accessdate=2014-08-02}}</ref> In August 2011, director [[David Yates]] and screenwriter [[Steve Kloves]], known for their collaboration on the ''[[Harry Potter (film series)|Harry Potter]]'' films, were hired to direct/write a multimovie version of ''The Stand'',<ref>{{cite web|last=McWeeny |first=Drew |url=http://www.hitfix.com/blogs/motion-captured/posts/exclusive-potter-masterminds-steve-kloves-and-david-yates-reunite-for-the-stand |title=Exclusive: Potter masterminds Steve Kloves and David Yates reunite for The Stand |publisher=Hitfix.com |date=2012-06-28 |accessdate=2012-07-02}}</ref> but left the project in October 2011, as Yates felt it would work better as a miniseries.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://whatculture.com/film/david-yates-says-hes-not-making-the-stand-because-it-should-be-tv-mini-series.php |title=David Yates Says He\u2019s Not Making THE STAND Because It Should Be TV Mini-Series |publisher=Whatculture.com |date=2011-11-12 |accessdate=2012-07-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120117171113/http://whatculture.com/film/david-yates-says-hes-not-making-the-stand-because-it-should-be-tv-mini-series.php |archivedate=January 17, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Both [[Ben Affleck]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Thompson|first=Anne|title=More Details on Ben Affleck in Snyder's Superman/Batman UPDATED|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/thompsononhollywood/be-affleck-is-the-new-batman-in-snyders-superman-batman|publisher=IndieWire|accessdate=2014-08-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203031502/http://blogs.indiewire.com/thompsononhollywood/be-affleck-is-the-new-batman-in-snyders-superman-batman|archive-date=December 3, 2013|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and [[Scott Cooper (director)|Scott Cooper]] dropped out over creative differences with the studio.<ref>{{cite web|last=Shaw|first=Lucas|title=\u2018Crazy Heart\u2019 Director Scott Cooper Exits Warner Bros.\u2019 Stephen King Adaptation (Exclusive)|url=http://www.thewrap.com/crazy-heart-director-scott-cooper-stephen-king|publisher=The Wrap|accessdate=2014-08-02}}</ref> On February 25, 2014, [[Josh Boone (director)|Josh Boone]] was hired to write and direct the adaptation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/fault-stars-director-talks-tackle-682033||title='Fault In Our Stars' Director in Talks to Tackle Stephen King's 'The Stand'|last=Kit|first=Borys|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=2014-02-25|accessdate=2014-09-10}}</ref> He later revealed that he wanted [[Christian Bale]] to play Randall Flagg and [[Matthew McConaughey]] for the role of Stu Redman.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/JoshBooneMovies/status/503313944413761536|title=I have always wanted McConaughey as Stu and Bale as Flagg. Still not sure how that story leaked \u2013 just not true.|author=Josh Boone|date=23 Aug 2014|publisher=Twitter}}</ref> By September 10, 2014, the script had been completed and pre-production was underway.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://collider.com/the-stand-movie-details-three-hour-cut-josh-boone/|title=Director Josh Boone On THE STAND, Fidelity to the Novel, Script Status, and Whether He'll Direct LESTAT|last=Cook|first=Tommy|work=Collider.com|date=2014-09-10|accessdate=2014-09-10}}/</ref> In November, Boone planned to split his adaptation into four full-length feature films in an effort to remain true to the breadth of King's sprawling novel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://smodcast.com/episodes/hollywood-babble-on-bonus-babble-on-hollywood-josh-boone-the-fault-in-our-stand/|title=Hollywood Babble-On Bonus: Babble on Hollywood: Josh Boone: The Fault In Our Stand|author=|date=|work=smodcast.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141120170433/http://smodcast.com/episodes/hollywood-babble-on-bonus-babble-on-hollywood-josh-boone-the-fault-in-our-stand|archivedate=November 20, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>Fleming Jr., Mike (November 21, 2014). [https://web.archive.org/web/20160221020603/http://deadline.com/2014/11/the-stand-stephen-king-josh-boone-four-films-1201291709/ \"Josh Boone Says Warner Bros Will Turn Stephen King\u2019s \u2018The Stand\u2019 Into Four Films.\"] ''Deadline''.</ref> In June 2015, Warner Bros. proposed an eight-part [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] miniseries to set up the story, which would culminate in Josh Boone's film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/447603-stephen-kings-the-stand-to-begin-as-eight-part-television-miniseries|title=Stephen King's The Stand to Begin as an Eight-Part Television Miniseries! - ComingSoon.net|date=June 5, 2015|work=comingsoon.net|accessdate=February 6, 2017}}</ref> However, in February 2016, ''The Stand'' project was put on hold and the rights reverted to CBS Films.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2016/02/josh-boone-stephen-king-revival-the-stand-the-fault-in-our-stars-1201694681/|title=\u2018The Fault In Our Stars\u2019 Helmer Josh Boone Pushes Back Stephen King\u2019s \u2018The Stand\u2019 To Next Direct \u2018Revival\u2019|last=|first=|date=February 2016|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, King talked of doing an extended TV series on Showtime or [[CBS All Access]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vulture.com/2017/09/stephen-king-on-movies-geralds-game-1922-it-the-stand.html|title=Stephen King on His New Netflix Movies, It, and His Big Year|last=Buchanan|first=Kyle|work=[[Vulture.com]]|date=September 25, 2017|accessdate=September 29, 2017}}</ref> In January 2019, a 10-hour limited series was ordered by CBS Television Studios to be broadcast on CBS All Access.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/stephen-king-stand-series-order-cbs-1203123968/|title=Stephen King\u2019s \u2018The Stand\u2019 Gets Series Order at CBS All Access|last=Low|first=Elaine|work=[[Variety.com]]|date=January 30, 2019|accessdate=January 30, 2019}}</ref> [[James Marsden]], [[Amber Heard]], [[Whoopi Goldberg]], [[Greg Kinnear]], [[Odessa Young]], and [[Henry Zaga]] were all in consideration for the roles of Stu Redman, Nadine Cross, Mother Abagail, Glen Bateman, Frannie Goldsmith, and Nick Andros, respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbr.com/stephen-kings-the-stand-casting-rumors/|title=Stephen King's The Stand TV Adaptation Reportedly Eyeing Some Huge Stars|last=Solis|first=Jorge|work=[[cbr.com]]|date=June 22, 2019|accessdate=June 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Comics===\n{{Main|The Stand (comics)}}\n[[Marvel Comics]] adapted ''The Stand'' into a series of six five-issue comic book [[Limited series (comics)|miniseries]].<ref name=\"rama1\">[http://forum.newsarama.com/showthread.php?t=150380 King: Marvel to Adapt The Stand as a graphic novel]{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, [[Newsarama]], March 17, 2008</ref> The series was written by [[Roberto Aguirre-Sacasa]] and illustrated by [[Mike Perkins]]. Colorist [[Laura Martin]], letterer [[Chris Eliopoulos]], and cover artist [[Lee Bermejo]] were also on the staff. The first issue of ''[[The Stand: Captain Trips]]'' was released on September 10, 2008.<ref name=\"MarvelAnnounces\">{{cite web |url=http://marvel.com/news/comicstories.3768.WW_Philly_2008%7Ecolon%7E_The_Stand |title=Wizard World Philadelphia 2008: Stephen King's The Stand |author=Stevens, Tim |date=2008-05-31 |publisher=Marvel.com |accessdate=2014-08-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100818014514/http://marvel.com/news/comicstories.3768.WW_Philly_2008~colon~_The_Stand |archive-date=August 18, 2010 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Music===\n[[Metallica]] derived the title for its song \"Ride the Lightning\" from a quote from ''The Stand''.<ref name=\"HowWeMade\">{{cite web |url=https://www.loudersound.com/features/metallica-how-we-made-ride-the-lightning |title=How We Made Ride the Lightning |author=Everley, Dave |date=2016-05-19 |publisher=loudersound.com |accessdate=2019-06-03|df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n[[The Alarm]]  had a song on the album [[Declaration (The Alarm album)|Declaration]]  called \"The Stand (Prophecy)\" as an homage to the book. The song contained certain lyrics directly related to the book, such as \"I met the walking dude, religious, with his worn out cowboy boots,\" and \"Hey Trashcan where you going boy?\"   \nThe main chorus of the song was \"Come on down and meet your maker, come on down and make the stand.\"\n\nThe title track to the album ''[[Among the Living]]'' by the band [[Anthrax (American band)|Anthrax]] is based on the novel.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{isfdb title|id=1148|title=The Stand}}\n* [http://www.bookpoi.com/the_stand_by_stephen_king_first_edition_identification.html Bookpoi]\u2014How to identify first edition copies of ''The Stand'' by Stephen King.\n\n{{The Stand}}\n{{Stephen King}}\n{{DarkTower}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stand, The}}\n[[Category:The Stand]]\n[[Category:1978 American novels]]\n[[Category:American post-apocalyptic novels]]\n[[Category:American horror novels]]\n[[Category:Biological weapons in popular culture]]\n[[Category:Novels about dreams]]\n[[Category:Novels about nightmares]]\n[[Category:Novels about religion]]\n[[Category:Fictional events]]\n[[Category:Novels by Stephen King]]\n[[Category:Novels set in the 1980s]]\n[[Category:Novels set in the 1990s]]\n[[Category:Novels set in Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Novels set in Atlanta]]\n[[Category:Novels set in Boulder, Colorado]]\n[[Category:Novels set in Indiana]]\n[[Category:Novels set in the Las Vegas Valley]]\n[[Category:Novels set in Maine]]\n[[Category:Novels set in Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Novels set in New York City]]\n[[Category:Novels set in New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Novels set in Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Novels set in Texas]]\n[[Category:Novels set in Vermont]]\n[[Category:Novels about viral outbreaks]]\n[[Category:Doubleday (publisher) books]]\n[[Category:Novels adapted into television programs]]\n[[Category:Demon novels]]\n[[Category:Novels adapted into comics]]\n", "name_user": "Doniago", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMusic:CN", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Stand"}
{"title_page": "Manfred Kielnhofer", "text_new": "{{short description|Austrian sculptor and photographer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name          = Manfred Kielnhofer\n| image         = Kielnhofer.jpg\n| image_size    = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = Manfred Kielnhofer\n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1967|01|28}}\n| birth_place   =  [[Haslach an der M\u00fchl]]\n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = \n| spouse        = \n| field         = Painting, photography, design, sculpture\n| training      = \n| movement      = \n| works         = [[Guardians of Time (Art)|Guardians of Time]]\n| patrons       = \n| awards        = \n| elected       = \n| website       = {{URL|kielnhofer.at}}\n| bgcolour      = \n}}\n'''Manfred \"KILI\" Kielnhofer''' (born January 28, 1967 in [[Haslach an der M\u00fchl]]) is an Austrian painter, sculptor, [[List of industrial designers|designer]] and photographer.\n<!--[[File:Kielnhofer.jpg|thumb|Manfred Kielnhofer]]-->\n[[File:Kielnhofer Time Guardians.jpg|thumb|Guardians of Time by Manfred Kielnhofer, Galerie Artpark Linz, 2006]]\n[[File:Franzoesischer Dom - Festival of Lights 2011.jpg|thumb|''Guardians of Time'', [[Festival of Lights (Berlin)]], [[Light art]], French Cathedral, Berlin, Velotaxi 2011]]\n[[File:Public contemporary-artbasel-ghost-car-manfred-kielnhofer.jpg|thumb|Public Art Project on Tour in Basel, ArtBasel, Design Miami / Basel, Liste, Scope, Volta, 2011]]\n[[File:Contemporary-art-biennale-show-project-venice- illuminations manfred kielnhofer.jpg|thumb|The [[Street art]] project \"Guardians of Time\" on tour in Venice, St. Mark's Square 2011]]\n\n[[File:Manfred kielnhofer interlux chair-.jpg|thumb|\"Interlux-Chair\", Lightart-object 2010]]\n\n[[File:Water-reflection-photographer-kielnhofer.jpg|thumb|Photographer Kielnhofer: Water reflection, 2009]]\n\n== Life ==\nManfred \"KILI\"<ref>[http://dip.mak.at/detail_designer.php?designer_id=1868 MAK Vienna Database] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102090259/http://dip.mak.at/detail_designer.php?designer_id=1868 |date=November 2, 2013 }}</ref> Kielnhofer visited the technical College [[Linz]] where he took his final exam in 1995. he was engaged with technique and design and art on building lead him to his special way of art. Since 2000 he lives as a freelance artist in [[Linz]]. 2005 he launched Gallery Artpark in Linz.\n\n== Work ==\nKielnhofer's most famous work is, \"[[Guardians of Time (Art)|Guardians of Time]]\". Drawing on religious and [[supernatural]] phenomena, the Guardians of Time are stone statues that are cloaked in hooded robes and situated to seem like they are moving forth in some kind of ritual. In some cases the figures stand alone; in other instances, they are grouped together as if whispering to each other. Kielnhofer places his statues in public places like ancient castles, old mines, plazas, and parks. They are installed and moved without fanfare, heightening the eerie, mystic aura they give off. The first of these mysterious figures was created in 2006. Since then, Kielnhofer continues to create and install these statues all over the world. In 2012, the artist created the first of a new series of miniature guardians out of plastic.<ref>[http://www.urbanghostsmedia.com/2011/02/guardians-time-mystic-sculpture-manfred-kielnhofer/] recalled at October 29, 2013</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Kielnhofer developed a new sort of 'act photographs', which involves the construction of a waterplate in his studio, where he can take photos of models sitting or lying down, likely on a mirror.\n\nIn 2010 he developed the concept of the [[Light Art Biennale Austria 2010]] with [[Martina Schettina]].<ref>[http://www.nachrichten.at/nachrichten/kultur/art16,456017 Ulrike Breit in: Lichtkunst-Biennale: International und heimisch, leuchtend und blinkend, O\u00d6N Kultur] recalled at September 13, 2010</ref>\n\nThe Interlux-Chair, Kielnhofers artwork shown at the biennial, was registered in the design-database of the [[Museum f\u00fcr angewandte Kunst Wien|MAK]], the Museum for Applied Arts in Vienna.<ref>[http://dip.mak.at/detail_product.php?designer_id=1868&search=%2Fsearchresult_product.php%3Fdesigner_id%3D1868%26amp%3Bstyle%3Dimage&object_id=7226&style=image MAK-Museum f\u00fcr angewandte Kunst Wien] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706093430/http://dip.mak.at/detail_product.php?designer_id=1868&search=%2Fsearchresult_product.php%3Fdesigner_id=1868&amp%3Bstyle=image&object_id=7226&style=image |date=July 6, 2011 }}(recalled at September 30, 2010)</ref>\n\nIn 2012 Establishment of the first miniature guardian. The mini guardian, limited edition, 54x36x34cm plastic.\n\nIn 2013 the first life-sized Guardian in bronze were cast at the art foundry Krismer.\n\nIn 2014 the large-scale sculptures 220x220x220cm guardians are shown by the [[Festival of Lights (Berlin)|Festival of Lights]] in Berlin.\n\nIn 2015 First works with the glass [[Berengo Studio]] Murano Venice.\n\nA fine empty coat were made of white [[Carrara]] [[marble]] by Studio Massimo Galleni in 2016.\n\nIn 2017 the Bike Guardian rider \u2013 time traveler started the tour.\n\n== Stipends ==\n* 2000 Studies in USA New York, Miami\n* 2005 Stipend of the county of [[Upper Austria]], Studio at the [[Egon Schiele]] Art Center [[\u010cesk\u00fd Krumlov|Krumlov]] CZ\n* 2007 Symposium \u2013 Egon Schiele Art Centrum \u2013 Cesky Krumlov 100 years after [[Egon Schiele]]\n* 2008 Symposium of sculpture on wood in Italy [[Ossana]] 2008\n* 2012 International symposium of sculpture Styria, Hartberg \"Slow!\"\n\n== Exhibitions ==\n* 2000\u20132005: Allerton Art Gallery New York, Gallery Tampere Finnland, Citygalerie [[Linz]], Giga Galerie [[Ansfelden]], filmproduction shadow performance main place [[Linz]], biggest children-painting of the world, Galerie Generali Group, Land-culture-project [[Enns (city)|Enns]]. Front-painting of an ancient house in [[Traun]].\n* 2006\u20132007: Gallery Artpark [[Linz]] \u2013 Skulpture garden Artpark, Gallery Fotopark [[Linz]], \"giant ball of integration\" on Tournee, Timeguards on tournee\n* 2008: [[Egon Schiele]] Art Centrum (CZ), Gallery Fontaine [[Amstetten, Lower Austria|Amstetten]], Black Box Gallery [[Copenhagen]]/Linz, art garden [[Graz]]; art in the public: Dianabad [[Wien]].\n* 2009: Cass Sculpture Fondation (UK), Art [[Vilnius]] together with [[Martina Schettina]], [[Franz West]] and [[:de:Herbert Brandl]],<ref>[http://www.artvilnius.com/images/ArtVilnius/files/jurenaite_about_artvilnius2.doc Art curator  Prof. Dr. Raminta Jurenaite about ART Vilnius \u201809] (recalled at July 8)</ref><ref>[http://www.artvilnius.com/images/ArtVilnius/files/press_release2.doc Press release Art Vilnius 09](recalled at July 8, 2009)</ref> Artfair Berlin-Arttower, Galerie Seywald Salzburg, Mobile-Galerie H\u00f6rsching, Woka Lamps Vienna\n* 2010: Castle Schloss Steyregg near Linz, Neuk\u00f6llner Kunstsalon Berlin, Galerie Kunst und Handel Graz, Kunstraum Ringstrassen, Light Art Biennale Lichtkunst 2010 Austria, Galerie Claudiana, Area 53 vienna, Citygalerie, Kunsthandel Freller\n* 2011: Galerie Thiele Linz, Nord Art Germany, Kunstprojekt \"ghost car\" zur [[Art Basel]], Liste, Scope, Volta Show, Festival of Lights Berlin, Grevenbroich Inseln des Lichtes, [[Kunsthaus Tacheles]] Berlin, Kunstverein Passau, ArtStays Ptuj Slovenia, Time guards on tour in Venice\n* 2012: Designmonat Graz, Galerie Bachlechner, Sculpture show Castle Hartberg \"Slow\", Ferryman Ferry Basel public Art Basel show, [[Occupy movement]] [[DOCUMENTA (13)]] Kassel Time guards, Festival of Lights [[Berlin]], Kunstmesse Linz Galerie Thiele, Art & Antiques fair vienna sculpture garden\n* 2013: Galerie Liebau Burghaun Fulda, Phantasten Museum Wien, Guardians of Time Settle in During Art Dubai, VBKW K\u00fcnstlerparade Stuttgart, Phantasten Museum Wien, public art show Venice Biennale, [[SCOPE Art Show]] Basel Galerie Kunst und Handel, Art Bodensee Galerie Galerie Bachlechner, Austrian contemporary sculptures castle Tabor, Festival of Lights Berlin, art and antiques vienna fair, Kunstmesse Fulda Galerie Liebau, IC contemporary Istanbul art project Galerie Kunst und Handel Graz vienna, Wikam Art&Antiques fair vienna sculpture garden Galerie Kunst und Handel, Art&Antique vienna Hofburg Kunsthandel Freller\n* 2014: Wiener internationale Kunst & Antiquit\u00e4tenmesse Kunsthandel Freller, Art&Antique Residenz Salzburg Kunsthandel Freller, Skulpturensommer Galerie Liebau, WIKAM im Schloss Laxenburg Galerie Szaal, Highlights Art Basel public art, Kunst in der Fabrik II im GIZ Rosegg Galerie Kunst und Handel, public art Brussels and Amsterdam, ART Bodensee Galerie Galerie, Art Stays Festival Ptuj Slovenia, Art Salzburg Kunsthandel Freller, Woodlands Waterway Arts Bench Competition, Texas USA, Festival of Lights Berlin, WIKAM Galerie Kunst und Handel, Art&Antique Hofburg Vienna Kunsthandel Freller\n* 2015: 56th [[Venice Biennale]] Of Art, Collateral Event \u2013 [[Personal Structures]], Time Space Existence, Palazzo Mora, [[TRIO Bienal]] Three-dimensional Rio de Janeiro Biennial, [[ArtPrize]] Grand Rapids Michigan USA\n* 2016: 4th Dubai art award, [[ArtPrize]] ArtPrize Grand Rapids Michigan USA, Aktionsraum Linkz, Susan Mains gallery Grenada, Galerie am Museum in Frauenau, Festival of Lights Berlin, Artigo Rio de Janeiro artfair, Light festival Kolding Denmark\n* 2017: Spotlight Festival Bucharest RO, Muralharbor Linz A, Museum Modern Art H\u00fcnfeld D, [[Guerrilla art]] [[documenta]] Kassel, ArtPrize Grand Rapids Michigan USA, Swell Sculpture Festival Gold Coast AU, Festival of Lights Berlin, Kunst Z\u00fcrich, Beijing China TaiKooLi mall\n* 2018: Toronto Light Fest, arte in fiera italia \u2013 Kunst und Handel gallery, Lightart Zwickau, Swiss Triennial Festival of Sculpture Bad RagARTz, PAN Awareness Projekt #TheEyeofGuardian Ghana Afr